I have never had a migraine before in my life  I felt OK 2 days after receiving the shot, however, on the 3rd day (4/5), I developed intense jaw pain and locking with muscle stiffness and headaches. For almost a week, I could not close my mouth all the way to chew. Once I was able to close my mouth again, it was painful to open it all the way for an additional week. All told, I had the headache and jaw pain/locking for 2 weeks total.  I was seen by a specialist but because the pain went away as mysteriously as it came, I am not currently under any medical care for this condition. It's notable that I had zero side effects from the second shot, which I got on 5/4. One thing I have noticed is that my jaw is tighter than it was before (but no lingering pain). I notice that I am grinding my teeth and that is not an issue I had prior to receiving the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Panoramic X-ray by both a dentist and a jaw/TMJ specialist. It was determined to be a muscular/spasm issue that was causing the pain and locking in my jaw. I was prescribed muscle relaxers, told to use moist heat, given jaw exercises to do and took Advil for pain, as needed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had what was suspected as a syncopal episode after receiving their vaccine. The patient syncopized in our observation area at 0835 after receiving the vaccine at 0830. The patient was witnessed sliding off their chair and onto the floor while they were reading the fact sheet on pfizer. It was suspected that the patient had anxiety while reading and had a vaso-vagal reaction, causing the subsequent syncopal episode. Patient vital signs post-syncope: BP 130/75, heart rate 73, 97% on room air. Patient was alert and oriented x4.  The patient was sat on a couch and had what was initially presented as another syncopal episode at 0847. Upon assessing the patient, I suspected that the patient had an atonic generalized seizure. The patient had slight decorticate posturing, with both arms abnormally suppinated towards his midline. The patient was slow to arouse. A 3 lead EKG was attached to the patient, with lead II showing normal sinus rhythm, no ectopy. Emergency medical services was called and arrived on-scene at 0904. The patient was assessed by Paramedics and decided to AMA with them. The patient stated that they will see their doctor.  The patient was advised to not operate any motor vehicles before being evaluated by their doctor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had - as soon as she gave me an injection - I felt like it was a little bit hot. I told her that. I knew I had a lot of allergies so I was being careful. Within a minute of sitting down, my right arm became swollen and bright red and felt burning and itchy. And it spread across my chest and went to my left arm. The rash or hives continued up my  neck up to my face and that all happened within first five minutes. Immediately after that, I had excessive coughing - couldn't cough up anything. I couldn't catch my breath and my throat started swelling a bit. they gave me 25 mg of Benadryl - capsule over the counter - and the 9-1-1 operator advised not to use the epi- pen. Paramedics came - gave me addition 50 mg of Benadryl - and they took me to the ER across the street and I was administered another 25 mg of Benadryl and also some steroid - Solumedrol - and after receiving these - then these symptoms went away. I continued on Benadryl and prednisone for a few weeks - the very next week - I had a large streak that went from injection site to left chest and I had a second red streak from left chest that ran down to my left arm. For two weeks, that burning fire rash would just come. No rhyme or reason as to when or why - arm, neck, chest, legs and sides. And I'd have to take extra Benadryl every time it would happen and I was still on the high dose of steroids as well. I also had - the next day - 24 -48 hours after vaccine - I had a severe headache and it lasted all day long. And about 24 hours after the vaccine- extreme fatigue, body aches and headache and weakness and that lasted for about three days. Fatigue lasted three to four weeks. Joint aches lasted three to four aches. Headaches have still continued. They have almost been worse actually. I had two headaches that I was so concerned about that would not go away - worst headaches I have ever had: one on May 1 and one on May 9 - and I took Maxalt and some Benadryl - the Benadryl did help a little bit (enough for me to go to sleep). Each headache lasted 12 -15 hours and they were the most severe headaches I had ever had. I didn't have anyone to take me to take me to hospital so I just tried to sleep. I saw my primary care doctor - virtual visit. I took the prednisone for two to three weeks. I still contend with the headaches.
LAB_DATA: Took labs - paramedics - for hospital ER - I have not gotten the results of those labs

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1935 received the first dose of Pfizer at 1935. At 1952, the client's partner approached the EMT table to report the client was complaining of his "heart racing." At 1955, the client's vital signs were as follows: heart rate 65, respiratory rate 12, O2 96%, and blood pressure 110/palpable (the client continued to move his arms during the blood pressure reading.) Per the client, he did eat breakfast that day, but no dinner, and he just drank some coffee. The client stated that he has no medical history, takes no medications, and has no allergies. At 2001, the client's heart rate was 70 and his O2 was 97%. The client stated that his symptoms had resolved at this time and refused Benadryl. The client stated that he wanted to go home and his partner stated she would drive him. Education provided regarding recommended 30 minute observation, AMR activation and emergency management,, and primary care follow up. The client left the building at 2005 accompanied by his partner, ambulating with a steady gait.

Patient initially hypotensive (prior to Trendelenburg) but all other vitals normal (73/44 BP, 99% RA, 84 Pulse, 14 Resp). Glucose was attempted but monitor not working. Patient observed closely by the NP and the Paramedic. Patient was no longer diaphoretic or pale, patient stated that he was feeling better after resting and eating. Patient is charted to have received a COVID vaccine on 4/8 with another company as well as two more doses with Embry Health on 4/11 and 5/10.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt. requested and received the J&J / Jansen COVID 19 vaccination yesterday at 1317.  While he was being monitored for any adverse reactions, Pt. asked if lightheadedness was a side effect of the shot.  Writer advised that it could be and that everyone is different.  Writer asked if he would like some water, and he declined. Pt. was advised to remove his mask so he could breathe better.  Writer took his pulse while I gathered information.  It was 96.  Pt. reported that he did eat lunch, is drinking plenty of water and fluids.  He relayed he is keeping food down and not having any other issues. Pt. is currently on opiate withdrawal protocol.  Writer asked about his breathing and his chest.  Pt. relayed he was not having difficulty breathing and denied any chest pain at all.  Writer spoke with the Deputy to be sure that we kept an eye on him for a bit longer after his 15 minutes while he was in his cell, due to his lightheadedness.  Pt. was talking with writer, answering questions with ease.  Pt. was not diaphoretic and did have good color.  His pulse was checked again, and it was 84. At 1333, when his 15-minute observation was done, writer went to assist pt. to his feet and informed him that I would escort him back to his cell because he was still feeling a bit uneasy.  When he stood, pt.'s knees buckled, and he knelt to the ground.  Writer helped pt. to lay down.  It was a smooth transition, and he had no injuries to his head or body.  Pt. had what appeared to be a short spell where his body completely tensed for a few seconds, then he relaxed.  He was having a hard time keeping his eyes open, but when prompted, was able to open his eyes.  The Deputy standing by was asked to call for the Public Health Nurses, who had moved on to the next POD to continue vaccinating.  Once on the scene, pt.'s blood pressure was obtained.  142/80.  His pulse was 82.  During this time, it appeared that the tensing episodes became more frequent and a bit more severe.  They were happening approximately every 30 seconds, and lasting between 5 and 10 seconds.  EMS was activated at approximately 1340.  Pt. was awake during these episodes, and communicated with the nurses attending to him. While attending to pt. and waiting for EMS, it was at that time that pt. admitted that this was not the first time this had happened.  He admitted that about a week ago, the same thing happened.  When that new information was explored, pt. reported that his wife thought he had "Serotonin Syndrome".  Writer asked what meds he was taking on the outside and he reported that he only takes methadone form the clinic.  He denied any other medications or street drug usage.  He does not take any mental health medications at our facility. Collectively, the nurses that attended to him after this episode agreed that this is an isolated incident and not related to receiving the COVID vaccine.  EMS arrived at approximately 1347, and report was given.  He was transported to the hospital for evaluation. Pt. was returned from the hospital at approximately 1600.  The Officer that accompanied him reported to facility that the hospital also believed this was an isolated incident, most likely related to withdrawals.  They did not believe that receiving the vaccine was a factor in today's events.  Labs were drawn at the hospital, and were all WNL.   Once back in custody, writer spoke briefly with pt..  He was feeling much better, and was sent back to his cell without further incident.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient began noticing increasing numbness in both lower extremities and was in the process of seeing a surgeon for lumbar spinal stenosis. She already had known DM neuropathy.  She received first covid vaccine on 3/4.  Lot # EN6199.  She received second vaccine 3/25 Lot # ER8732.  She reported five days later having bilateral leg spasms.  She presented to the ER with inability to walk or move her legs and numbness from her belly button down on 4/27/2021. Thoracic MRI shows demyelinating lesion at T1-T4.  Also noted to have epidural lipomatosis at T5-6 with mild to moderate spinal cord compression. Diagnosed with transverse myelitis. LP completed, Brain MRI and cervical mri completed.  No evidence of MS, no infectious or neoplastic process evident as a cause thus far. Anti mog and NMO negative.  It's not certain if the demyelinating lesion occurred because of the vaccine, but thus far, no other cause has been found.  Treated with 5 day course of IV steroids.   She remains unable to walk.
LAB_DATA: Brain, cervical, thoracic and lumbar MRIs. Lesion T1-4.  LP- performed to rule out infections, MS, and neoplastic process. B12 level 310, folate 7.0, A1c 6.0.   Additional labs for Lyme, ANA, Ace level, RPR, TSH and HIV are pending.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When I received the 2nd dose of the vaccine, I was 26 weeks and 3 days pregnant. My estimated due date is 07/10/2021. I received the vaccine mid-morning on 4-6-2021. The following day (4-7-2021), I experienced arm soreness, fatigue, muscle aches, and chills. Those symptoms were subsiding by the evening of 4-7-2021. Early in the morning of 4-8-2021, I was wakened from sleep because my heart felt like it was beating too fast and too hard. This experience was most intense when lying on my left side, and at its most intense, I felt like I couldn't quite catch my breath. Sitting upright seemed to slow my heart rate. Walking caused it to increase again, and I felt more winded than usual walking short distances. I contacted my OB-GYN when her office opened on 4-8-2021 and told her what I'd been experiencing, and she instructed me to go to the hospital to be evaluated. I was admitted and monitored in Labor and Delivery continuously all day. My heart rate was elevated. My fetus's heart rate was normal. I had an EKG which was normal. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the 1st COVID Pfizer vaccine, lot #EW0182 and use by date is 05/13/21 at 0930am. Co-Lead Vaccinator, RN, EMT, and EMT observer,  responded to the patient who stated, " I have the sensation to clear my throat, almost as if there is this pressure in my throat,"  at 0925.  The patient was sitting in the gravity chair and airway was patent, respiratory rate was regular and even with no signs of labored breathing. The patients vitals were taken at 0926 and were as follows: 118/74 ( right arm, sitting upright), 80 bpm, and RR of 15, and alert and oriented to person, time, place, and situation. Lead vaccinator, gave the patient diphenhydramine (Benadryl) 50mg, liquid suspension, PO at 0930. The client was placed in the supine position in the gravity chair. The patient denied difficulty breathing, shortness of breath, itching, dizziness, headaches, or nausea. The patient was talking in full sentences and was in no apparent distress. The patient stated, " The pressure in my throat is getting better, I just want to swallow is all." Vital signs were all within normal limits at 0935: 126/80 (right arm, sitting upright), 80 beats per minute, respiratory rate of 14 breaths per minute, 100% oxygen saturation. At 0940, the patient continued to state, " I just have the sensation to swallow." The patient was placed in fowler's position. The patient continued speaking in full sentences, oxygen saturation levels remained at 100%.  The patient stated, " I prefer to be sitting upright," so the patient was then placed in a sitting upright position in the gravity chair. At 0951, the patient's vital signs were 126/80, 68 beats per minute, 100% oxygen saturation, and 14 respirations per minute.  Patient was able to swallow without difficulty and no distress was observed. Patient verbalized hx of being afraid of needles and has no pertinent medical history. Patient denied having any chronic medical conditions and was on progesterone and estradiol for hormone replacement therapy. At 1000, patient's vital signs were 118/80 (right arm, sitting upright), 70 beats per minute, O2 sat of 100%, and RR of 15 breaths per minute. Patient was instructed about ER precautions. Gave patient V-Safe information, and reported occurrence in VAERS. Instructed patient to inform nurse of previous reaction to the first dose of Pfizer. Patient left site at 1002 with family member who provided transportation.
OTHER_MEDS: Herbal Supplements: Valerian Root; Estrogen; Progestin

Saturday evening May 1 I met with nine friends (all vaccinated) and ate a lot of food, drank moderately, and then did not sleep well. Approximately noon the next afternoon (Sunday, May2) while driving I noticed a developing dry-cough, chest congestion, and general fatigue. While camping that night I had some chills, thought I might have a bit of a fever, and had little appetite. I arrived home Tuesday, May 4 coughing a lot and very fatigued. Wednesday morning I went in for a Covid test. My cough and fatigue continued to increase along with muscle pain and headache. Wednesday night my fever topped out near 104. It broke and I felt much better but for the next few days (until around May 11) it fluctuated between normal and around 100-102. The Covid test came back negative but I went back for another just in case. It too came back negative. My temperature has now stabilized, the cough and congestion are mostly gone. I'm still a bit tired but feeling much better. It seemed like a case of Covid without the Covid. I am glad I got vaccinated but that was rough.

I gave her an ice pack to put on her throat and was observing her when the itching started on her abdomen. I advised her she was having an anaphylactic event and she denied me calling ambulance or using epipen. Around 4:05 pm she asked for some cream so we gave her some hydrocortisone cream OTC that she applied to itchy area on chest and throat and she said she was feeling better. Around 4:15 she told me the itching was starting inside her mouth and allowed me to call 911 and administer one dose of epinephrine 0.3 mg in her left thigh. The fire department came around 4:20 and started talking to her and taking vitals. blood pressure was 146/90 and heart rate was 100 even with the epinephrine causing her to shake. They advised she wait for emt's that arrived around 4:30 pm and they conviced her to go in the ambulence to the hospital even though she was feeling fine since there was a chance the epi would wear off and she would need more help.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot # EW0182, expiration date 05/13/2021 at 0930) at 11:20AM. On 05.12.21, client was found by EMT sitting upright and complaining of chest tightness/sensation s/p vaccine administration approx. 30 mins later. Client is a 27 year old female, alert and tracking. Initial VS: BP 128/78, pulse 74, RR 12, O2 sat 99% and fully oriented. EMT advised client to remain additional 30 mins to monitor VS and symptoms to which she agreed. Client denies any pertinent medical history. She states has allergy to antibiotics but not specific to which. This is the client's first dose of the Pfizer vaccine. Assessment revealed no swelling, hives, discoloration, shortness of breath or other signs of anaphylaxis. Airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Her remaining vitals at 1210  - 124/72, pulse 72, O2 99% respirations 14. At 1215, BP 126/74, pulse 72, RR 14, sat 99%. At 1220, BP 128/76, pulse 72, RR 12, sat 99%. At 1225, BP 122/74, pulse 70, RR 14, sat 99%. Client reports resolution of chest tightness after initial set of vital signs and denies any other symptoms. At 1230, BP 126/76, pulse 72, RR 14, sat 99% and continues to be fully oriented.  Client was registered for V safe and provided with vaccine relevant information. Client was instructed to seek medical attention if a life-threatening reaction occurs later in the afternoon or evening. Client left facility ambulatory with steady gait. Client declined any further intervention or EMS activation.

I received the COVID Vaccine at 12:30 PM. My temperature had been increasing all afternoon along with my heart rate. At roughly 8:40 PM, my temperature increased dramatically to approximately 38.9C. This may have happened over a relatively short period of time, since it was 37.9 C at approximately 8:00 PM. My heart rate increased to 150 bpm and I became dizzy. After a minute, my heart rate decreased to roughly 115 bpm.  Unsure whether to call EMS or not, I called a friend, who is a Dr. at the local hospital (Dr. is a colleague we do research together.) Dr. was concerned but provided information on what to do and when to call EMS or be driven to the ER. I spent the rest of the evening with a pulse between 105 and 110 and my temperature hovered around 38.9C until at least 12:30 AM.   The next day, my heart rate had decreased to roughly 80 bpm and my temperature to approximately 37.8C. I spent most of Tuesday sleeping. Today (Wednesday May 12, 2021) my heart rate is down to roughly 76bpm. My temperature is holding around 37.2C.   I have reported this to the CDC through the COVID vaccine reporting app.   My resting pulse is usually 62 bpm with a waking pulse of 58-60. My normal temperature is 36.5-36.7C. I have a wellness exam schedule for Monday. Dr. is not my regular GP, but was available at a time when my regular doctor was not available.

Client  received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot # EW0182, expiration date 5/13/2021) at 1455. The client complained of feeling hot, nausea, spotty vision at. EMT and RN responded at this time. The client was offered a bottle of water. He appeared pale and clammy, and was speaking in 1-2 word sentences. The client denied chest pain or shortness of breath. At 1506, the client stated that he was feeling "weak and faint" and was transferred to the zero gravity reclining chair at that time. The client denied any medical history, stated he takes no medications, and has no allergies. The client stated he ate breakfast at 1000 and hadn't had anything to eat or drink since then. At 1509, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 100/60, heart rate 52, respiratory rate 20, O2 97%, temperature 96.3 (the client was still quite sweaty at the time.) The client's pulse was thready but regular. The client continued to appear diaphoretic but his color was improved. He was alert and oriented. The client stated his arms were tingling but his vision had returned to normal and his nausea had resolved. The client refused benadryl at this time. At 1517, the client's heart rate was 84, respiratory rate 14, pulse strong and regular. The client's skin color had returned to normal and he was no longer diaphoretic. The client stated that his symptoms had all resolved and he was feeling "back to normal." Education provided regarding v-safe, primary care follow up, symptom management, AMR activation and emergency management. At 1530, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 100/82, heart rate 72, pulse strong and regular, O2 96%. The client was able to stand up from the reclining chair without any dizziness, and ambulated with a steady gait to his car, where he drove himself home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Starting Sunday, May 2nd around 5pm, I noticed a pain in my back near my right shoulder blade.  It started small ? just when I would stretch my right arm out, but as the time went by, it began to hurt from that starting spot going up my back into my neck, into my right arm, around the right side of my chest and down the right side front of my chest.  I took 2 ibuprofen which seemed to do nothing.  When I went to bed around 10pm, it became hard to move without pain, so I took 4 ibuprofen and a OTC sleeping pill.  I slept very restlessly, as any movement caused a lot of pain.                                                                                                  ?On Monday upon waking, I could not get out of bed without pain.  There was so much pain any way I would move, and found to get out of bed, I had to get onto my stomach, and slide out of bed like a snake.  Again, I took 4 ibuprofen hoping to have some relief, but it really didn?t do much.  Any movement that would make the muscles on my right side move, would cause a great deal of pain.  Just to lift my right arm, I had to do so using my left hand to lift my right arm.  Any movement at all was painful.  This continued all day.  I tried also switching ibuprofen to extra strength acetaminophen which did not help.  By the time I went to bed I could barely move.  Again, I went to bed with 4 ibuprofen and an OTC sleep aid.  Another restless painful night of sleep was the result.    ?Tuesday upon waking I felt better until I tried to get out of bed.  The pain was back and I found that I again I had to slither out of the bed on my stomach.  This time I took Excedrin Migraine as I found a migraine headache looming.  Taking this was the first true relief of pain.  Although I had twinges of discomfort, I didn?t have the extreme pain when I moved.  I was relatively good for the rest of Tuesday and Tuesday night.  As I felt I had some improvement in pain relief, I did not take any OTC meds.    ?This morning when I woke, I again found I could not sit up, push myself up or anything other than gingerly rolling onto my belly and sliding out of bed again.  I took a hot shower, letting the water beat down on my back, which seemed to help some and followed it up with 4 ibuprofen.  Currently I?m doing better, I can move without a lot of pain, but I do get the occasional jab of pain in my neck/shoulders/right arm/back (just beneath the right shoulder blade).     I know this sounds like an odd reaction, however I did not do anything that would have caused this issue with my muscles.  On Sunday I tossed a frisbee to my 6 year old grandson for about 10 minutes, and planted one planter with flowers.  I cannot think of anything different in my life other than this vaccine.  No new exercise, no new meds, no new anything.  Over a week prior to this vaccination, I was lugging large bags of mulch and potting soil with no issues whatsoever, so I find it hard to imagine that tossing a frisbee could cause this kind of pain.

Patient woke up on March 11 with vomiting and diarrhea, continued feeling ill through to the morning of March 15, when he was found to be lethargic and unable to communicate. I took him to urgent care where he was immediately rushed to the hospital emergency room at local hospital. He went into cardiac arrest for 20 minutes while in the ER.  Besides the cardiac arrest patient presented with the following: Acidosis, acute renal failure, acute respiratory failure, shock, severe sepsis, septic shock, sepsis, right ventricular enlargement, pleural effusion bilateral, pericardial effusion, etc... Patient was in ICU and on a ventilator for 1 week, then 5 days in telemetry. He was released when stable as a diagnosis could could not determined. Discharge instructions were to follow up with primary care Dr for additional tests. Patient was discharged on March 26, 2021. He went to hospital March 30 for blood work for a primary care appt on April 2. Patient's blood pressure was again very low and his sodium level was dangerously low, he was again admitted to the hospital. After exhaustive tests it was determine he has Addison's autoimmune and Hashimoto's autoimmune diseases. He was discharged from hospital on March 5, 2021. Patient was put on hydrocortisone, fludocortisone, and levoxothorine. He is now doing fine on the medication.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had cataract surgery a few years ago, and after that had successful YAG laser capsulotomy due to clouding of the "capsule" holding the artificial lens.  About 2 weeks post 2nd COVID shot, right eye vision deteriorated markedly with lots of blurring.  Had eye exam 3/11, diagnosed as needing YAG laser capsulotomy on Right eye for post-cateract capsular clouding -- successful.  By 3/31, left eye vision deteriorated markedly (blurred vision) and continued to deteriorate as determined by eye exams on 4/21 and today, 5/12.  Diagnosis is that I once again have a "membrane" clouding the capsule -- and I will have YAG surgery again. Normally YAG capsulotomy surgery does not have to be repeated. My eye doctor says a repeat of this condition is very rare and, when it happens, only in young people. The fact that these two events (right eye, then rare left eye capsular clouding issue in both cases needing YAG capsulotomy) happened beginning about  14 days or so post the second COVID shot was remarkable. I know that correlation does not equal causation, but my eye doctor also told me today that she has seen some other eye issues due to possible hyperactive immune responses stimulated by the COVID vaccine. Thus I am reporting this via VAERS just in case others might be reporting similar issues. My YAG surgery for the repeat left eye capsulotomy will be scheduled soon.
LAB_DATA: Eye exams on 3/11, YAG Laser capsulotomy surgery right eye 3/17, post op3/31, another vision check 4/21, another vision check 5/12, YAG laser surgery left eye to be scheduled

SYMPTOM_TEXT: As I left my father's manufacturing facility where I received the shot, I felt a little bit of a sore throat, but I thought I was just being paranoid. The next day, my sore throat continued (I am prone to sore throats), and I was fatigued, had some body aches, and had a pounding headache. I took a 30-minute nap throughout the day to relieve some fatigue (which is not something I normally do), and about 26 hours after the shot I took a pain killer (Sorry, I can't remember which kind) to attempt to alleviate the headache, but it didn't help much. The next day, I was totally fine.   This is all a very small price to pay for some protection from COVID-19. I just wanted to share the information in case it is useful to you.
PRIOR_VAX: A few years ago, when I  was in my mid-20s and started getting flu shots regularly, I had flu-like symptoms after receiving the
ALLERGIES: None, just seasonal allergies to dust and mold as well as allergies to rodents (rabbits, hamsters, etc.)

After 48 hours and regular doses of ibuprofen, my fever came down to 100 where it stayed between 99 and 100 for the following 24 hours. The muscle aches slowly subsided. My injection arm continued to be very sore and tender and feels inflamed and hot. Today, five days following the injection, my arm is still very sore, hard and hot.

Client received the 1st dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine lot # EW0182 and expiration date 5/13/21 at 4:50PM.  Client's son approached PHN near security station to report something wrong with his mother. PHN arrived to observation area to find client seated upright alert and oriented x 4.  Client reports she just felt like fainting a few minutes ago.  Client reports she felt dizzy, heat and heaviness in her legs from the thigh down, and palpitations at the time she felt like she was going to faint. Client reports to  PHN that she did not eat.  Client reports she has no medical history, no known drug allergies and takes no medications. At 5pm vitals: blood pressure:155/84, pulse:80, and oxygen:98%. Client reports she usually has blurred vision when she reads, when asked if she had blurred vision. Client clarifies she needs glasses for reading. Client reports no shortness of breath, no chest pain, no headache and no current dizziness.  PHN offer client water, client accepted water. At 5:09PM  vitals: blood pressure:172/83, pulse:74, and oxygen:100%.  Client reports "feeling fine." At 5:14pm  vitals: blood pressure:140/90, pulse:81, and oxygen:100%.  Minutes before taking vitals client reports feeling heaviness in legs and heat and palpitations and dizziness for a few seconds. PHN  offers calling paramedics. Client reports no chest pain, no shortness of breath, no headache and  resolving of previous symptoms. At 5:17pm client reports that if she does not eat she will feel shaky and weak.  At 5:21pm vitals: blood pressure150/90:, pulse:70, and oxygen:100%. Client reports no chest pain, no headache, no dizziness, no trouble breathing, Client states that she "feels good."  At 5:30pm vitals: blood pressure:158/90 and pulse:77 and oxygen: 100%.  Client reports "feeling good." alert and oriented x4.  Provided client with ER precautions and discussed several options to either call paramedics, have family take client to urgent care or emergency room or to continue to monitor for 15 more minutes. Client decides to stay 15 more minutes and to keep monitoring blood pressure.  At 5:35pm vitals: blood pressure:158/90, pulse:80, and oxygen:100%. Client denies having any symptoms just feels worried since her 9 year old daughter has not eaten yet. Informed client she does not need to stay and can leave if she wants to.  Client stays the full 15 minutes. At 5:40pm vitals are blood pressure:162/89, pulse:76, and oxygen:100%. Client denies any chest pain, dizziness, headache. Provided client with ER precautions again and recorded all blood pressures on a separate paper so client could discuss with primary care provider.  Client walked out with a steady gait at 5:48PM.

The patient did have her first COVID-19 vaccine approximately 3 weeks ago. She was due for her second dose of the vaccine this coming Monday. She denies any severe fevers at home. No shortness of breath, no chest pain.  She was brought in for observation and started on dexamethasone.   Hospital Course:   Remained under observation and did not require any supplemental oxygen.  He tolerated her diet and did not feel weak or fatigued.  She denied any chest discomfort.  I recommended that she postpone getting her second Covid vaccine until she is entirely cleared of her Covid infection. At that time, I reentered the store and told them of my frightening symptoms and they asked me to wait until I felt better. In this time,  blood pressure was checked by (excellent) staff and pharmacist that gave the shot, and it was low but rose to normal within the hour and I was able to make the short drive home. she gave it down towards her knee on her leg; injection was very painful/some burning during the injection; injected the area swelled up as she gave it and became red; injected the area swelled up as she gave it and became red; had a flare for the past couple of days/pretty bad flare/ put her into a flare/ Feeling really bad; This is a solicited report from a non-Pfizer sponsored program (marketing program name not available) from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer from Amgen , license party for etanercept (ENBREL). This non-serious solicited report was reported to Amgen on 05Apr2021 by a consumer from a commercial program and involves a 27 year old female patient who gave it down towards her knee on her leg (PT: product administered at inappropriate site), injection was very painful (PT: injection site pain), injected the area swelled up as she gave it and became red (PT: injection site swelling and PT: injection site erythema) while receiving Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. No historical medical condition was reported. The patient's current medical condition included rheumatoid arthritis. No concomitant medications were provided. No co-suspect medications were reported. The patient began Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector on 04Apr2021. On 04Apr2021 last night, the patient took her first injection of Enbrel last night and when she injected the area swelled up as she gave it and became red. The patient reported injection was very painful and she recounted that she gave it down towards her knee on her leg. On 05Apr2021 same day of this report, the patient reported it was sore but no longer red. The patient was referred to HCP and arranged for an in home patient training for next injection. No treatment information was received. The outcome of the event injection site pain was reported as not recovered/not resolved. The outcome of the event injection site erythema was reported as recovered/resolved. The outcome of the events product administered at inappropriate site, injection site swelling were reported as unknown. The event injection site erythema was resolved on 05Apr2021. Action taken with Enbrel and Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was reported as unknown for the events injection site pain, injection site swelling and injection site erythema. The causal relationship between the events injection site pain, injection site swelling, injection site erythema, product administered at inappropriate site and Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was not provided by the consumer. The reporter declined consent for follow up. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected. Causality Assessment for the events Pain during injection, Injection site redness, Injection site swelling, per Company (Amgen): related. Causality Assessment for the event Product administered at inappropriate site, per Company (Amgen): Not related.  The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the events with the suspect product was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  Follow-up (12Apr2021): This is a follow-up solicited report from a non-Pfizer sponsored program (marketing program name not available) received from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer from Amgen, license party for etanercept (ENBREL).  ADDITIONAL INFORMATION RECEIVED ON 12/APR/2021 AND 20/APR/2021: This case was upgraded to serious case. In this follow up, it was reported that the patient had a flare for the past couple of days/pretty bad flare [PT: rheumatoid arthritis], some burning during the injection [PT: injection site pain] while receiving Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. It was previously reported that the patient first injected close to her knee and had a bad injection experience with immediate pain and swelling at the site. On unknown date in APR/2021, the patient stated that for the past couple of days she had a flare especially in her hands. On 12/APR/2021, the patient stated that she did her injection higher on the thigh to ensure a subcutaneous injection and she had no swelling or pain. On 16/APR/2021 (Friday of last week), the patient had a pretty bad flare that subsided on the weekend prior to her last injection. On 19/APR/2021, the patient injected in her thigh and she had some burning during the injection that lasted for about a minute afterwards. The outcome of the events rheumatoid arthritis and injection site pain were reported as recovered/resolved. The event injection site pain was resolved on 19/APR/2021. The event rheumatoid arthritis was resolved on an unknown date in APR/2021. Action taken with Enbrel and Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was continued for the event rheumatoid arthritis. The causal relationship between the event rheumatoid arthritis, Enbrel and Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was not provided by the consumer. The reporter declined consent for follow up. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.   The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the events with the suspect product was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  Amgen Comment: This individual report does not change the safety profile of the product.    Amgen Causality Assessment: Rheumatoid arthritis flare up, Product administered at inappropriate site assesses as unrelated while Injection site redness, Injection site swelling, Pain during injection assessed as related to etanercept.  Follow-up (26Apr2021): The following clarification was received from Amgen to clarify the route of administration of Enbrel, included: The event reported was Product administered at inappropriate site "gave it down towards her knee on her leg [PT: product administered at inappropriate site" & "when she injected the area swelled up as she gave it and became red." Following the initial dose that was administered inappropriately, "On 12/APR/2021, the patient stated that she did her injection higher on the thigh to ensure a subcutaneous injection and she had no swelling or pain" The reporter declined consent for follow up. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.  Follow-up (27Apr2021): This is a follow-up solicited report from a non-Pfizer sponsored program (marketing program name not available) received from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer from Amgen, license party for etanercept (ENBREL).   ADDITIONAL INFORMATION RECEIVED ON 27/APR/2021: The outcome of the previously reported event rheumatoid arthritis was updated to recovering/resolving. Action taken with Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector for the previously reported event rheumatoid arthritis was updated to not applicable. In this follow up it was reported that the patient experienced a flare/ feeling really bad [PT: rheumatoid arthritis] while receiving Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. The patient's co-suspect medication included COVID-19 (corona virus disease-2019) vaccine. On 25/APR/2021, Sunday, the patient received her second dose of COVID (corona virus disease) vaccine. So, the patient skipped a dose of Enbrel therapy. Then on 26/APR/2021, yesterday of this report, the patient felt really bad. She thought the vaccine put her into a flare. She was doing a little better today. She would restart Enbrel later today and switched her injection day to Tuesday. She also mentioned that this time, she didn't have a flare at the end of the week, as she had with her prior dose. So, she thought that without the COVID vaccine, she would had been fine. The outcome of the event rheumatoid arthritis was reported as recovering/resolving. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.  Amgen comment: This individual report does not change the safety profile of the product.  The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the events with the suspect products etanercept and BNT162B2 (reported as "COVID vaccine") was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  Amgen's Causality Assessment: The events Pain during injection, Injection site redness, Injection site swelling were related to etanercept. The events Rheumatoid arthritis flare up, Product administered at inappropriate site were unrelated to etanercept.; Sender's Comments: The reported events of injection site pain, injection site swelling and injection site erythema were assessed as possibly related to etanercept based on temporal association and known drug safety profile. Reported event rheumatoid arthritis flare is an intercurrent medical conditions and is unlikely related to Enbrel.  Pfizer comment: Confirmed the Amgen assessment for Enbrel. The reported events were assessed as not related to BNT162B2. The events preceded, most of them already recovered, at the time of vaccine injection.

The patient medical history included a history of allergies all her life and asthma attack following flu vaccination 20-25 years prior so she did not take another one again. The patient was not given any other vaccine on the day of COVID-19 vaccination, had not received any other vaccine 4 weeks prior and had no history of any other prior immunization. Family history was none. Stated that she takes the normal medicines she always take, Pepcid and Prilosec for her stomach, Breo for breathing sometimes and the Zyrtec for when her allergies act up. The patient stated that she took Covid-19 vaccine because she wanted to be protected, protect her husband, who is not in good health, family and community. There was a hot rush to the face, her tongue started to sting all over that went to the roof of her mouth and lips. They felt like they were swelling, but she had no swelling of lips or mouth. The stinging slowed up and it didn't continue, and it gradually went away. They monitored her for a couple of hours maybe and she got out about 2pm. She got her shot at 11am. She stated that she has an allergist in the city and her previous allergist has retired last March so she was now seeing other allergies virtually. The patient stated she had a little numbness in the face, nose, and mouth, nothing dramatic, no stinging. Again, she mentioned her face was still a little numb, but there was no stinging, tingling, or swelling. They told her to monitor it for 12 hours and if it occurs again to contact her doctor or go back to emergency room. Doctors encouraged her to contact Pfizer to report this. She had allergy shots for the past 15 years, but was unable to provide the names, NDC, lot or expiry for allergy shots. She has not had any allergy shots for the past couple (2) months. The patient stated she was unable to provide NDC, lot or dose of Zyrtec she took on 28Jan2021. She stated that she had to end up taking 2 of them (Zyrtec). She took one in the morning (on 28Jan2021) about 8am and the other around 11am after the COVID-19 vaccine. No further details provided. She went to the emergency room due to the events. The outcome of the events became hot, thought she was having hot flashes/There was a hot rush to the face and stinging of tongue that went to the roof of her mouth and lips was recovering and the outcome of the event hypoaesthesia was not recovered. The action taken with Zyrtec and unspecified allergy shots was dose not changed.

The patient received the first COVID shot on 26Jan2021 and didn't really have a reaction, but soreness in the arm a couple of days. He then started having back pain and he is a very active person so he didn't think anything of it. Spouse told him that he needs to see the doctor because she thought he had shingles. They do not know if it's associated to the COVID shot or not. They need to also cancel his appointment for tomorrow because the doctor does not want him to get his second COVID shot since he is on medication for the shingles. Mentions again, his arm was a little sore, but then 4 days after that he had back pain. He is an exceptionally active person, and excavation construction worker and still works and so he thought it was just a pulled muscle. Then a few days later, pain was awful and area was sensitive to touch and it looked a little swollen and he had nothing else. A couple days later he kept saying it bothered him and it was all the way around to his side. It was fine at first it started with a little rash and so he went to the doctor today and diagnosed with shingles. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of shingles which included valacyclovir (Was given Valacyclovir 1 gram tablet to take three times daily to help the shingles). The outcome of the event "soreness in the arm" was recovered on 28Jan2021, for Back pain and shingles was not recovered, for "so he thought it was just a pulled muscle" was unknown. Among the Vaccine recipients, mild-to-moderate pain at the injection site within 7 days after an injection was the most reported local reaction, with less than 1% of participants. In general, local side effects; the ones you get on the arm where you got the shot (such as injection site redness and injection site swelling) were mostly mild-to-moderate in severity and resolved within 1 to 2 days. Side effects that you may experience throughout the rest of your body; (systemic side effects) including fever and chills were observed with the first 1 to 2 days after vaccination and resolved shortly thereafter. Swollen lymph nodes (lymphadenopathy), which generally resolved within 10 days, is likely to have resulted from a robust vaccine-elicited immune response. Chest feels strange; Shortness of breath; Affected breathing; Immune system doesn't work well; Bedridden due to the pain; Very low energy; Lump nodules were swollen under chin and underarms; Trouble moving around doing normal tasks; Tingling in face, hands, and feet; Tired quickly; Feel full; Underarm lymph nodes and chin lymph nodes were hurting; Bedridden due to the pain; Face swollen; Body temperature 102 and 104; Joints still hurt greatly/sore joints/joints hurting; This is a spontaneous case, initially received from other non-health professional via agency (reference number: SEQ20-00719) on 24-Feb-2020 with an additional document received on the same day (being processed together), concerning a 64-year-old, female patient.  The patient's relevant medical history included increased body mass index (BMI), cigarette smoker, allergy to ciprofloxacin, sulfadiazine and dexlansoprazole, vitamin B12 deficiency disease, bladder muscle dysfunction - overactive, diverticular disease of colon, obstructive sleep apnea syndrome, mixed hyperlipidemia, mild intermittent asthma, spinal stenosis of lumbar region, nicotine dependence, panacinar emphysema and tobacco dependence in remission. The patient had two surgical procedures bilateral oophorectomy and hysterectomy.  The patient's past medications included unspecified flu shot, Zoster vaccine live (varicella zoster vaccine live), Pneumococcal 13 valent vaccine (pneumococcal vaccine 13v), Pneumococcal 23-polyvalent vaccin (pneumococcal vaccine polysacch 23v) and Tdap (diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular, tetanus vaccine toxoid).  The patient's concomitant medications included ranitidine, oxybutynin, Symbicort (budesonide, formoterol fumarate), budesonide;formoterol, amlodipine and Albuterol (salbutamol) all for unknown indication.  On 04-Oct-2019, the patient was administered with Flucelvax Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261222, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] for unknown indication. It was reported that no other medication was given at the time of shot.  On the same day, ever since (as reported) after vaccination, the patient's chest felt strange.  On 05-Oct-2019, one day after vaccination, the patient's face became swollen just a little, but she went to a play. By the end of night after vaccination, the patient developed sore joint and had temperature of 102. The patient took Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid).  On 06-Oct-2019, reported as Sunday, two days after vaccination, the patient was bedridden.  On 07-Oct-2019, reported as Monday, three days after vaccination, the patient's temperature was 104 while joints, underarms lymph nodes and chin lymph nodes were hurting. The patient went to emergency room (ER) and was given unspecified intravenous (IV) steroid therapy and to her physician who discharged her the same day with diagnosis of adverse reaction to influenza vaccine. The vital signs showed blood pressure 122/89 mmHG. No laboratory tests for vaccine were performed. Assessment and Plan included scheduled tests on radiology: Bone density (BD), hip and bone spine (BS) on 06-Jan-2020, X ray chest 2 views post anterior (PA) and lateral (LAT) standard protocol on 09-Dec-2019, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of brain with contrast completed on 13-Dec-2019 and mammogram (MG) screen bilateral with tomosynthesis (Tomo) and coronary artery disease (CAD) standard protocol on 06-Jan-2020.  On an unspecified date, after vaccination, the patient's lump nodules under her chin and underarms were swollen. Most days, the patient had trouble moving around and doing normal tasks. Some days, the patient was bedridden due to the pain. It has affected patient's breathing, tingling in face, hands, feet. Also, the patient's joints still hurt greatly and shortness of breath was still an issues. The patient had very low energy, felt full, got tired quickly and her immune system didn't work well anymore. The patient stated that other physicians didn't known how to treat an adverse effect of a vaccine, so she was going to the medical facility, but Covid-19 came out. The patient was taking unspecified probiotics NOS, lots of vitamin C (ascorbic acid) and Elderberry (sambucus nigra) for what she believed that kept her going.  At the time of this report, the patient had not recovered from the events of 'mobility decreased', 'bedridden', 'pain', 'chest discomfort', 'tiredness', 'shortness of breath', 'immune system disorder (NOS)', 'energy decreased', 'arthralgia' and 'feeling abnormal'. The outcome of the events 'swelling face', 'swollen lymph nodes',  'lymph node pain', 'body temperature increased', 'tingling', and 'abnormal breathing' was not reported.  The reporter assessed the events as related to Flucelvax Quadrivalent, according to physician's diagnosis.  Follow up information received from other health professional on 05-Jun-2020: New reporter added and race updated. Batch number was confirmed while expiration date was confirmed as unknown. Start date for the events of 'swelling face', 'bedridden' and 'painful joints' was updated. New events of 'lymph node pain', 'body temperature increased', 'chest discomfort', 'tiredness', 'shortness of breath', 'immune system disorder (NOS)', 'energy decreased' and 'feeling abnormal' added. Treatment measures with Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), unspecified probiotics NOS, vitamin C (ascorbic acid) and Elderberry (sambucus nigra) added. Ranitidine, oxybutynin, Symbicort (budesonide, formoterol fumarate), budesonide;formoterol, amlodipine and Albuterol (salbutamol) added as concomitant medication. Vaccine facility information updated while blood pressure measurement and body temperature added as laboratory tests. Medical history updated for increased (BMI), cigarette smoker, allergy to ciprofloxacin, sulfadiazine and dexlansoprazole, vitamin B12 deficiency disease, overactive bladder, diverticular disease of colon, obstructive sleep apnea syndrome, mixed hyperlipidemia, mild intermittent asthma, spinal stenosis of lumbar region, nicotine dependence, unspecified colon disease, panacinar emphysema, tobacco dependence in remission and two surgical procedures bilateral oophorectomy and hysterectomy. The case and all events changed from medically confirmed as 'NO' to 'YES'. Event Trouble moving around doing normal tasks recoded to 'movement disorder' and therefore case downgraded. Narrative amended accordingly.  Significant case correction performed on 14-Jul-2020: The event of Trouble moving around doing normal tasks was recoded from LLT: Movement disorder to LLT: Mobility decreased. The narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: The patient experienced swelling face, chest discomfort, respiration abnormal, lymph node pain, body temperature increased and arthralgia after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. On an unspecified date, after vaccination the patient also developed lymphadenopathy, mobility decreased, pain, bedridden, paraesthesia, dyspnoea, asthenia, feeling abnormal, immune system disorder and fatigue. The patient's relevant medical history included increased body mass index (BMI), cigarette smoker, diverticular disease of colon, obstructive sleep apnea syndrome, mixed hyperlipidemia, mild intermittent asthma, spinal stenosis of lumbar region, panacinar emphysema and tobacco dependence in remission. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events cannot be excluded and is assessed as possibly related except for lymphadenopathy, mobility decreased, pain, bedridden, paraesthesia, dyspnoea, asthenia, feeling abnormal, immune system disorder and fatigue, which is unassessable.; Reporter's Comments: The events are assessed as 'adverse reaction to influenza vaccine'; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced swelling face, chest discomfort, respiration abnormal, lymph node pain, body temperature increased and arthralgia after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax Quadrivalent. On an unspecified date, after vaccination the patient also developed lymphadenopathy, mobility decreased, pain, bedridden, paraesthesia, dyspnoea, asthenia, feeling abnormal, immune system disorder and fatigue. The patient's relevant medical history included increased body mass index (BMI), cigarette smoker, diverticular disease of colon, obstructive sleep apnea syndrome, mixed hyperlipidemia, mild intermittent asthma, spinal stenosis of lumbar region, panacinar emphysema and tobacco dependence in remission. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events cannot be excluded and is assessed as possibly related except for lymphadenopathy, mobility decreased, pain, bedridden, paraesthesia, dyspnoea, asthenia, feeling abnormal, immune system disorder and fatigue, which is unassessable.

Tightness in chest; Difficulty breathing/ breathing issues; The patient started feeling like she had the flu/like she had a case of an awful flu; All over itching; Rash all over/rash on face, head and trunk and itched; Rash all over/rash on face, head and trunk and itched; Fluad Quadrivalent contained neomycin and hydrocortisone - two ingredients that the patient has a severe allergy to; This spontaneous case was received on 17-Sep-2020 from a pharmacist via agency (reference number: SEQW20-01883) with additional information (reference number: SEQW20-02245) on 23-Sep-2020 (being processed together) and concerned a 76-year-old, female patient.   The patient's current conditions included long list of allergies (some severe) including allergy to steroid, neomycin, yellow dye and hydrocortisone. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.  On 08-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: left deltoid] (explicitly coded as 'Contraindicated drug administered') as protection against seasonal influenza. The batch number was 279790, expiry date: 25-May-2021.  On the same day, at the evening, the patient started feeling like she had the flu and was all over itching. She had tightness in her chest, severe symptoms such as rash all over and difficulty breathing. The rash was primarily on her face, head and trunk and itched severely. The patient experienced pain all over her body and in her joints, experienced severe fatigue, felt weak all over and had chest pain. Upon examining the ingredients, after the reaction occurred, the patient realized that Fluad Quadrivalent contained neomycin and hydrocortisone, two ingredients that the patient had a severe allergy to.  On 09-Sep-2020, the patient went to health clinic  and was given Tylenol (paracetamol) for the pain, Albuterol (salbutamol) inhaler for difficulty breathing and Atarax (alprazolam) for itching.  On 23-Sep-2020, She was still using a nebulizer for her breathing issues and the chest pain and was in a lot of pain all over. The patient also reported that her head and face still had a rash and itch from time to time, and that she was still experiencing an overall weakness, like she had a case of an awful flu.  At the time of initial reporting on 23-Sep-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events.  The reporter assessed the event to be related to Fluad Quadrivalent. Patient wanted to know if there were any tests they could run to see if she was still having an immune reaction to the vaccine she had received.  Case updated on 10-Nov-2020: Correction made to information received on 17-Sep-2020: Vaccine indication recoded from 'flu prophylaxis' to 'influenza immunization'. Narrative was amended. The patient's current conditions included long list of allergies (some severe) including allergy to steroid, neomycin, yellow dye and hydrocortisone while concomitant medications were not reported. Began seeing zig-zags and transient flashes of light in the peripheral vision of her left eye/vision issues; Ocular migraine; Body aches; Headache; Gastrointestinal issues (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea); Gastrointestinal issues (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea); Gastrointestinal issues (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea); Feeling ''not like her usual self"; This spontaneous case was received on 18-Sep-2020 from other non-health professional via agency (reference number: SEQW20-01989) and concerned a 60-year old, female patient.   The patient's concurrent condition included Hashimoto's disease. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.   On 04-Sep-2020, around 2 pm, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular and anatomical location: left arm) for protection against seasonal influenza. The batch number was not reported.   On the same day, around 7 pm, the patient began seeing ''zig-zags'' and transient flashes of light in the peripheral vision of her left eye. She was also experiencing body aches, gastrointestinal issues (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea), and a headache.   On 05-Sep-2020, the patient stated that the issues started lessening somewhat, but she was still experiencing vision issues and the headache, and still feeling ''not like her usual self''.   On 06-Sep-2020, patient stated that she was feeling better, but still seeing the flashes of light in the peripheral vision of her left eye.  On an unspecified day, reported as presently, patient states she was experiencing a minor headache and body aches, diarrhea, and transient flashes of light in the peripheral vision of her left eye. Patient had also seen an ophthalmologist, who stated that there were no issues with her retina and suggested that the vision issues may have been caused by an ocular migraine. Patient will have a follow-up appointment with the ophthalmologist soon.  On an unspecified date, the outcome of the events vomiting, nausea, and feeling abnormal was resolved.  At the time of initial reporting on 18-Sep-2020, the outcome of the events headache, body aches, diarrhea, 'visual flashes', and migraine was not resolved.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.   The reporter assessed the case as non-serious.  Company comment: A 60-year-old female patient was administered Afluria Quadrivalent. On the same day, five hours later, the patient developed photopsia (Began seeing zig-zags and transient flashes of light in the peripheral vision of her left eye), pain, headache, nausea and vomiting. Patient had also seen an ophthalmologist, who stated that there were no issues with her retina and suggested that the vision issues may have been caused by an ocular migraine. Causality is assessed as possibly related for pain, headache, nausea and vomiting. For the events of ocular migraine and photopsia, causality was highly confounded by patient's concurrent condition, Hashimoto's disease. However, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. A warm feeling in lower back; Chest has a dull ache; Could not move and had to hold to the shelf; Chest felt like it was caving in; A huge pain in the spine; Pain on the right side below rib cage; This spontaneous case was received on 21-Sep-2020 from other non-health professional (consumer) via agency (reference number: SEQW20-02007) and concerned a 68-year-old female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included hypertension and type 2 diabetes (T2D). The patient's past vaccination history included flu shots before without any issues. The patient's concomitant medications included carvedilol, Bupropion (bupropion hydrochloride), Synthroid (levothyroxine sodium) and metformin, all used for unreported indications.  On 18-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, MF59; dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location: upper left arm- deltoid, and route of administration: intramuscular) for flu prevention at pharmacy. The batch number reported was 279790 and expiry date was 25-May-2021. This was the patient's first senior shot. After getting vaccinated the patient was able to walk to other side of the pharmacy.  On the same day, while the patient was still in the store, within minutes after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient developed a warm feeling in lower back and a huge pain in the spine. In addition, the patient could not move and had to hold to the shelf. The patient was not sure how long she stood there and then she walked back to the pharmacy and sat down. The pharmacist measured the patient's blood pressure and it was high (could not tell how high). Also, the patient's chest felt like 'it was caving in'. Ten minutes after, the pain went away, but the patient's chest had a dull ache.   On 19-Sep-2020, one day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient referred having pain on the right side below the rib cage. The patient did not receive any treatment measures associated with the events.  On an unspecified day in Sep-2020, the patient recovered from 'chest ache' and 'pain localised'. The patient referred having no pain.  The outcome of 'localized feeling of warmth' and 'chest abnormal feeling of' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Fluad Quadrivalent.  The reporter assessed the events as non-serious.  Company comment: A 68-year-old female patient was administered Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine. On the same day, after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient developed chest pain, chest discomfort, feeling hot, mobility decreased and spinal pain. One day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient referred having pain (on the right side below rib cage). Causality was confounded by patient's current conditions, hypertension and type 2 diabetes, and multiple concomitant medications. More information regarding diagnostic findings is needed. However, with information available causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. The patient's concurrent conditions included allergy to thimerosal and other preservatives. The batch number and expiration date were unknown.  On the same day, less than 12 hours after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine, the patient had a severe headache and aching pain in her upper arm that spread through her shoulder and to her upper back.  On 17-Sep-2020, within 48 hours of receiving Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine, the patient developed an allergic red blotchy rash over most of the truck of her body, the sides of her neck and her upper thighs.   On the same day at 4:30 pm, the patient visited her doctor who confirmed that the patient was having an allergic reaction and advised her to take Benadryl (diphenhydramine hydrochloride) and Pepcid (famotidine) to reduce the effects.  On the same day, later that evening as reported, the patient's skin in the areas of the rash began to feel prickly and irritated by clothing brushing against it. The patient was advised to take Benadryl (diphenhydramine hydrochloride) topical cream which had been ordered.  At the time of initial reporting on 21-Sep-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events.  The reporter assessed the events as adverse reaction after receiving the Fluad (65+) vaccine. On the same day, the patient was vaccinated with varicella zoster vaccine (reported as 'shingles vaccine') (brand not specified, indication, dose, route of administration, anatomical location: arm). The batch number was not reported. It was reported that these immunizations were given in separate arms.  On 25-Sep-2020, in the middle of the night, the patient experienced a fever of 101.5 Fahrenheit. Also, the patient experienced sore throat and headache. The patient's arm in which she received the shingles vaccine was painful, but there was no injection site pain in the arm that she got the influenza vaccination.  On an unspecified date in Sep-2020, the patient contacted CVS to inquire if she should get a COVID test, because of her symptoms. They did not recommend it at that time but advised that should get a COVID test if the symptoms persisted for more than a few days.    On 26-Sep-2020 and 27-Sep-2020, the patient took Advil (ibuprofen) for temperature and it went away.   On an unspecified date in Sep-2020, the patient recovered from fever.   On 28-May-2020, reported by Monday, headache and sore throat were resolved.    The outcome of the event 'painful arm' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.   The reporter assessed the case as non-serious  Company comment: Pain in extremity (reported as 'arm in which she received the shingles vaccine'), pyrexia, oropharyngeal pain and headache were associated with the use of the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. The events occurred the same day after vaccination with the product making chronology suggestive for all events. Also, on the same day when our product was given, the patient was vaccinated with varicella zoster vaccine and the arm in which she received the shingles vaccine was painful, but there was no injection site pain in the arm that she got the influenza vaccination. The patient's current condition included high blood pressure while concomitant medications included lisinopril used for unreported indication. There was also concern of the patient regarding COVID infection, but this was not confirmed. With information presented, causality is assessed as unlikely related for all events (except for pain in extremity which is assessed as unrelated) having in mind chronology, suspicion on COVID and report of another co-suspect product. The injection site had a red square, the size of a large band aid. It was also warm to touch; The injection site had a red square, the size of a large band aid. It was also warm to touch; The site of injection was sore/it was very painful; 56-year old patient was given Fluad Quadrivalent; Hasn't been able to sleep properly; This spontaneous case  was received on 01-Oct-2020, from other non-health professional via agency (reference number: SEQW20-02680) and concerned a 56-year-old, female patient.  The patient's medical history included hypertension and thyroid problems. The patient's concomitant medications included losartan, levothyroxine, aspirin low dose (acetylsalicylic acid), and probiotic unspecified, all used for unreported indication.   On 28-Sep-2020, patient was vaccinated with unspecified Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Inappropriate age at vaccine administered') for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number reported was 279808, expiry date: 30-Jun-2021.  On the same day, after the administration of Fluad Quadrivalent, the site of injection was sore.  On an unspecified date in 2020, the patient hadn't been able to sleep properly, because she was not able to lay on that arm side in the bed.   On 29-Sep-2020, on Tuesday, the injection site had a red square, the size of a large and aid. It was also very painful and warm to the touch, but not hot.  On 01-Oct-2020, it was reported that it hadn't gone away, but it had improved a little bit, and it was not as red as before. However, it was still sore. Despite that, the patient could still use her arm.  At the time of initial reporting on 01-Oct-2020, the patient was recovering from the events 'vaccination site warmth', 'vaccination site erythema' and 'vaccination site pain'. The patient was not recovered from the event of 'sleep difficult'.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The reporter assessed this case as non-serious. Company comment: A 56-year-old patient developed insomnia, vaccination site warmth, vaccination site pain and vaccination site erythema within one day after vaccination with the suspect product, Fluad Quadrivalent. High BP (systolic around 200mmHg); Loss of balance; Difficulty breathing/shortness of breath; Disorientation; This spontaneous case was received on 05-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional (consumer) via agency (reference number: SEQW20-02933) and concerned a 76-year-old female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included hypertension, hypercholesterolemia and type 2 diabetes (T2D). The patient's concomitant medications included losartan, hydrochlorothiazide, Ozempic (semaglutide), metformin and ezetimibe, all used for unreported indications.  On 02-Oct-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, MF59; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular and anatomical location: left upper arm) for flu prevention. The batch number was 279812 and expiry date was 30-Jun-2021. It was the first time that the patient got vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent.  On 03-Oct-2020, one day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient started feeling difficulty breathing, shortness of breath and developed high blood pressure (BP) (systolic around 200mmHg). In addition, the patient experienced disorientation and loss of balance. After, she went to the urgent care and started feeling better when she arrived there. Electrocardiogram (ECG) revealed that the patient had no abnormalities. The patient did not receive any treatment associated with the events.  On an unspecified date in Oct-2020, the patient visited her healthcare provider.  At the time of initial reporting on 05-Oct-2020, the patient was recovering from the events. The patient reported being better.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Fluad Quadrivalent. The patient reported an adverse side effect she experienced after having her Fluad vaccine.   The reporter assessed the events as non-serious.  Company comment: Blood pressure systolic increased, balance disorder, dyspnoea and disorientation were associated with the use of the suspect product - Fluad Quadrivalent. Causality is assessed as unrelated for blood pressure systolic increased since the patient suffers from hypertension and for other reported events causality is assessed as unlikely related due to suggestive chronology and presence of confounding factors, concomitant medications. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upset; Patient received Fluad Quadrivalent instead of 'high dose' influenza vaccine; This spontaneous case was received on 06-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional via agency (reference number: SEQW20-03031) and concerned an elderly male patient of an unknown age.   The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.  On an unknown date in 2020, nurse practitioner recommended to the patient to make sure that he got a high-dose influenza vaccine. The patient called several pharmacies in the area to see if they had a 'high-dose' influenza vaccine and was told that they did.  On 06-Oct-2020 before administration, the patient confirmed that he was receiving a 'high dose' influenza vaccine with pharmacist.  On the same day, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and indication: not reported) instead of a 'high dose' influenza vaccine (explicitly coded as 'Wrong vaccine administered'). The batch number was not reported.  On the same day, when the patient got home and looked at the paperwork, however, patient saw that he received Fluad Quadrivalent. He did not experience any issues post vaccination, but he was very upset that he did not receive the vaccine that his healthcare provider had recommend he receive, despite he verified with pharmacist that this was what he received.  The outcome of the event was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The reported assessed the case as non-serious.  Company comment: Anxiety was associated with the use of the suspect product - Fluad Quadrivalent. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. According to the narrative wrong product was more likely a result of upset state than received vaccine therefore causality is assessed as unrelated to the product but more likely related to medication error. Wrong product administered is assessed as unrelated per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Anxiety was associated with the use of the suspect product - Fluad Quadrivalent. On the same day, the patient was vaccinated with non-company co-suspects Pneumovax 23 (pneumococcal vaccine polysacch 23v; dose, route of administration, anatomical location, indication and batch number: not reported).  On 25-Sep-2020, one day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent and Pneumovax 23, the patient had chills and horrible body aches. Patient received second covid shot from technician certified to vaccinate. Tech knocked on door, because when patient went to stand she felt like putting her head between her legs and fainting. I went in there and it looked like previous episodes of fainting I have seen so I tried to calm her and have her breath while patient was getting the blood pressure machine. Patient then fainted again a little more intensely, but still not alarming me that much. She came to and again I was talking with her to try to keep her alert. I asked her how she was feeling. She said she was extremely hot (she kept repeating this), that she had a headache, and asked for water. I told her we couldn't give her food or water until she felt better. We now had blood pressure monitor on her and it wouldn't read her pressure or pulse it kept saying error. I just used it on another patient with high blood pressure and it had been functional. I had been manually holding her pulse and it was strong and normal. Then she fainted again and started shaking. the shaking quickly stopped. She woke up and said that she couldn't see.  I asked tech to call 911, while I stayed with her and kept assessing her. Tech got the headset got 911 on the phone and turned the phone over to me. I asked her to grab another blood pressure monitor. We tried again and at 3:55pm it was 88/50 and pulse of 66. I was talking 911 and responding to all questions over the phone. I had to ask the patient for the responses (many COVID related questions). I told the lady her blood pressure and the lady said I don't need to know any of that. She wanted me to keep asking the patient questions. The blood pressure was 87/49 and pulse of 65 at 3:58. Now the EMT had arrived and assessed her. They said she fainted and she said she did not want to go with them. So they left. The patient remained at pharmacy for 45 to 90 min more until she was sure she felt okay enough to catch an uber home. I called her at 8:43pm and she said she feels much better, has eaten, and is with her boyfriend in case she experiences anymore ADRS. Upon asking who her primary physician is she said she last saw a doctor in another country.  She said her md only speaks another language. I asked her to call her MD and report to her in a different language what happened since I am unable to speak with her.
LAB_DATA: Blood Pressure 88/50 pulse  66 at 3:55pm; 87/49 pulse 65 at 3:58 by pharmacist.

After four days with no noticeable side effects or problems, I laid down for the night & noticed that my heart seemed to be struggling a great deal as in it seemed to be pounding hard, racing, & along with arrhythmia.  This continued with a severe & continuous struggle around the clock, but more extreme throughout the night.  I at first thought maybe I had some dehydration, but this did not seem to be the case.  I was diagnosed with light Tachycardia in 1987, but have never experienced anything like what has happened since the COVID-19 vaccine.  I searched the internet & noticed there are reports of other people suffering with the same issue & that a country has opened an investigation related to these heart struggles resulting in Myocarditis following the vaccine.  I am under the care of a cardio Dr. in a city who prescribed Metoprolol ER Succinate 50 mg  1 x daily, ordered a 30 day event monitor which just arrived in the mail, & has ordered an MRI, along with some lab work.
LAB_DATA: Tests are not completed at this time:  30 day event monitor which was just received, a heart MRI, & lab work

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 6-7 hours after receiving the vaccine, I started to develop hives around my body, including on feet, stomach, ears, face, back, and legs. I had fever and chills, muscle aches, joint pain,  headaches,  and nausea later that night as well. The next morning, my left eye was swollen, left side of tongue completely swollen, lips swollen, and left side of throat closed (anaphylaxis). I took prednisone, Benadryl, and Tylenol to relieve the symptoms, and the swelling around my left eye, tongue, throat, and lips went away. Throughout the day, more hives have developed around my body and face, including my right eye.  I am continuing to take Benadryl and Tylenol and finish doses of prednisone. The fever and chills, muscles aches, joint pains, hives, headache, and nausea are still present.
