4/30/21: This patient comes in complaining of worsening low back pain.  She has a history of severe degenerative disease in his had surgery.  She was scheduled to see her neurosurgeon last year however it got canceled due to the COVID-19.  Patient states she saw her neurologist on Tuesday and was given injections which significantly helped.  She states that her pain has returned however.  She has had no trauma.  No footdrop.  No difficulty with her bowel or bladder.  Patient states she only uses Tylenol arthritis at home.  5/1/21:The patient is a 70-year-old female presenting to the emergency department for back pain.  She has a history of chronic back pain and states that has been worsening.  She was recently seen here for the same complaint.  She currently rates her pain 10/10 intensity.  She reports that she has chronic numbness and tingling of her bilateral arms/hands and legs/feet.  She states that this is also worsening.  She denies any changes in bowel or bladder function or perineal numbness.  She states that she has been using a walker at home and that she has tried to make an appointment with her neurosurgeon who previously operated on her but that she has been unable to get through to their office.  She reports that she only called 1 time on a Friday.  She is taking Tylenol at home for her pain and reports minimal relief.  She denies any fevers or associated concerns at this time.  5/2/21: This is actually her 3rd visit in less than a week with this complaint.  She was seen 2 other times at a outside facility.  She states that she had back surgery about 10 years ago at Beaumont.  She states she was supposed to see her neurosurgeon last year but this did not occur secondary to COVID-19.  Her primary care physician had referred her to a neurologist did some injections ahead some relief of her back pain for a week or 2 but this is since worsened.  She states that over last several days she has had increasing numbness and tingling in her feet as well as increasing weakness of her lower extremities as well as some now some new incontinence of urine when she stands up.  She today she also complains some chest pain she attributes more from just amount of pain he has from her back.  She rates her back pain as a 10/10 intensity.  She did have 1 episode of a week or 2 ago where she slipped down and fell on her knee but did not hit her back directly.  She did not hit her head.  She describes the chest discomfort in her upper abdomen lower chest area.  She is nauseated but not vomiting here.  She denies any exertional dyspnea or orthopnea prior to this.  She has had no recent fever chills.  5/11/21: The patient is an 70 y old female admitted on 5/4/2021.  The patient was originally seen by Neurology on 05/07/2021 when she presented with diffuse weakness.  She has a history of hyperlipidemia, hypertension and diabetes.  The patient at that time described the acute onset of weakness ascending from the feet, then involving the legs and arms also associated with sensory symptoms that started about 2 weeks prior to her presentation.  She also had persistent neck and back pain radiating to her arm and legs limiting her ability to walk.  On neurologic examination at that time the patient had absent deep tendon reflexes in the lower extremities and trace reflexes at the biceps.  She had significant weakness in the lower extremities and mild weakness in the upper extremities.  She also had a dysarthric speech.   Given the patient's CSF analysis showing protein elevation to 266 with no pleocytosis, wbc's were only for, there was support for a clinical diagnosis of acute inflammatory demyelinating poly radicular neuropathy or such variant.    The patient was started on plasmapheresis and has received her 2nd session of plasmapheresis on 05/09/2021.  She will have a total of 5 sections, one every other day.  The patient also has hyponatremia, this can be seen in about 5% of patients with Guillain-Barre syndrome, we also do see pseudohyponatremia but this is in patients that have received IVIG.

Patient presents to Urgent Care for evaluation of a vaccine reaction.  He went to his primary care physician, for a Prevnar 23 vaccine on Monday, May 10 at approximately 10 AM.  He reports having a Prevnar vaccine in 2019 without any problem.  He has not had any other vaccines within the last 2 weeks and has never had a COVID-19 vaccination.  He admits that they did hold pressure at the injection site since he is on a blood thinner and he has not appreciated any swelling at the injection site or bleeding. Later that evening at 7:30-8:00 pm he developed chills, rigors, arm swelling at the injection site and a oral temperature of 99.7.  He took Tylenol and went to bed with some improvement in his symptoms.  Since then his arm has become red, swollen extending downward from the injection site.  It did have some itch to it but now it has become more circumferential and painful causing him to seek evaluation.  His pain is aggravated by palpation and the symptoms were improved with Tylenol originally but continued to worsen now.  He is on Tikosyn and Eliquis so he is unsure of what he can take for his symptoms.  His symptoms are moderate in severity, rapidly worsening and persistent in nature. On physical exam he has 16 x 27 cm erythema and warmth with pain to palpation distally to the  injection site that is well appearing without hematoma, erythema or pain.  Erythema is almost circumferential in nature and arm measures 32 cm at the time of exam. Neurovascularly intact with compartments soft.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Starting around 9 PM, I had chills and felt my temperature going up. By 10:30, I had more than full body chills. They were like full body spasms that made it hard to breathe. My fever went to 103 degrees. I tried to sleep, but it was extremely difficult.  I did finally sleep, I woke up and I had difficulty managing my body, hands, and brain. I lost bladder control. I took my temperature and it was 104. Went back to bed with difficulty. I woke up a couple more times with the same result. However, I didn't have the brain power to take my temperature again. I could barely find the light switches and almost went into the closet instead of the bathroom. (That's what my husband told me) 8 or 9 am,  my fever was down to 102 degrees, my head felt like someone was splitting it open and my body felt like I had bruises from head to toe. I was awake  MAYBE  an hour all day that day. My lungs were on fire and I was short of breath again. It was like I was recovering from COVID pneumonia again. My doctor prescribed prednisone for my lungs.  My right arm had a reaction below the injection site. It was swollen and hot. My left arm that had gotten the first injection also started hurting again. It was also swollen and hot.
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol, Lisinipril, Allopurinol, vitamin D, Fish Oil

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the injection and was told to wait for 15 minutes. Shortly after receiving the shot, I had to use the restroom, so I asked if it was ok to do that before I sat for the 15 minutes. As I was walking to the bathroom, I felt a warm tingling sensation go through my arms (almost as if I could feel the injection going through my veins) and then the sensation traveled down my legs and my heart started RACING. This all happened within two to three minutes after receiving the shot. At first I just thought it was odd, but as I kept walking my heart rate continued to skyrocket and I did not like the way I felt. I went to the EMTs and they laid me down and hooked me up to a blood pressure machine. My blood pressure was significantly elevated (which is very unusual for me). As someone with neurocardiogenic syncope, my blood pressure typically drops - the way I felt was not at all in line with a syncopal episode.  My heart rate remained elevated while at rest, but did come down a little bit after about 20  minutes; my blood pressure would also  come down a bit while at rest but as I would lift my head (even just a little bit) to drink something my blood pressure and heart rate would again sky rocket. This went on for 1.5 hours. After about 2 hours, I was finally able to sit up without my blood pressure and heart rate going through the roof, but I felt simply awful. For the next two weeks I felt light headed (as if my head was detached from my body) and dizzy. I couldn't get out of bed in the morning without drinking a gatorade as I felt so weak and shaky. I developed significant heart palpitations that lasted for a solid month.  Additionally, I am someone who has always gotten a period at 27-28 days. I had my regular period two days after vaccination (which was when it was due), but then I got it again 16 days later. That has never before in my life happened to me. Not during illness or times of high stress.  Somehow I had a significant reaction to this vaccine and my cardiologist advised that I do not get the second.
LAB_DATA: EKG Stress Test Echocardiogram Halter Monitor - 24 hour
OTHER_MEDS: Daily multi vitamin Vitamin D3 - 1000 Magnesium - 300mg
HISTORY: Neurocardiogenic syncope - happens with trauma or with illness. Significant cardiac inhibitory response when it does occur - heart usually stops for approximately 15 seconds with each event.

Slowly over the course of four days (Friday to Monday) I continually felt "off" but differently than others explained post-vaccine (not necessarily flu like). This was an extremely high heart rate (up to 130+) and palpitations, chect pains, and calf discomfort. Finally on Monday, March 1, I went to my primary doctor because I felt so off and I knew something was wrong.  My doctor sent me to the ER where they found a new DVT in my upper leg. This time it was deemed unprovoked, though it was right after the second vaccine.

I was told the first was 'provoked' by pregnancy and a long flight. The patient received her second Covid 19 vaccination on March 11 but was experiencing some myalgias.  She had multiple sick contacts at home with COVID-19 infection.  Unfortunately she had diarrhea and poor p.o. intake and developed dehydration.  She came to the emergency department for further evaluation after she had her vital signs at home and saw her heart rate was elevated and her blood pressure was low.  She was found to have a sinus tachycardia with hypotension upon arrival despite the fact that she has been holding her blood pressure medications for several days.  She was hypokalemic.  Covid swab came back positive.  She was given IV fluids and potassium was replaced her blood pressure remained on the lower side.  She was admitted to the hospital and started on steroids.  She met criteria for remdesivir and convalescent plasma with saturation at 90% on room air on the second day of her admission.  She completed a 5-day course of remdesivir.  She was given a unit of convalescent plasma.  Her potassium normalized.  Her heart rate normalized.  She had a better oral intake.  Metoprolol tartrate was started on a lower dose for blood pressure and heart rate control.  Her blood pressure remained in the normal range off her lisinopril and Norvasc.  She does have history of Leiden 5 and with a history of DVT and takes Xarelto.  She had a D-dimer which was checked which was normal.  She continued on her Xarelto as an inpatient. Twelve days after receiving the second dose of Moderna, I started feeling an itching sensation in my left inner ankle around 7pm Monday night. By 6:00am the next morning (Tuesday, May 11), the itching became intense and had spread to both ankles and both legs below the knee. Numerous raised red bumps developed along the inside of both legs below the knee as well the ankles. They looked very similar to mosquito bites or bedbug bites but both of those possibilities has been ruled out through process of elimination. The itching became very intense and almost unbearable. The bumps became swollen. Most about 1/4" in diameter to as large as 1/2" in diameter. They are bright  red with  white halos. A very intense continuous burning itching sensation continued through the day, that night, and the next morning. Today (Wednesday, May 13) the itching seems to be subsiding.

Chills     HPI 79-year-old female, history of COPD for which she wears oxygen at night and as needed, also with a history of leukemia and obesity who presents to the ED complaining of generalized body aches, fevers up to 103, feeling generally unwell and weak, poor sleep, onset 3 to 4 days ago.  Patient reports that she received her second COVID-19 vaccine approximately 1 week ago.  Tolerated this without any particular symptoms.  She has had 2 days of watery/nonbloody diarrhea.  Does admit to nausea with several episodes of vomiting earlier today.  She is denying any particular abdominal pain.  Does believe she felt her urine burning earlier today but has had no gross hematuria.  Denies any flank pain.  No ill contacts although her husband has been at home with a slight cough.  Patient does have a cough presently but it is nonproductive.  She is denying any particular chest pain or subjective shortness of breath.  No rash or unusual lower extremity pain, swelling, or redness.    ED to Hosp-Admission Discharged  4/6/2021 - 4/17/2021 (11 days) Hospital  Last attending ? Treatment team Severe sepsis (CMS/HCC) Principal problem Discharge Summary Internal Medicine    Inpatient DeathSummary   BRIEF OVERVIEW Admission Date: 4/6/2021     Discharge Date: 4/17/2021  DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY   Presenting Problem/History of Present Illness/Reason for Admission Patient is an 79 y.o. female morbidly obese with past medical history of chronic lymphocytic leukemia follow-up that was initially scheduled oncology follow-up for April 7 now postponed to the next 2 weeks, COPD on 2 L oxygen support at home, GERD, depression and anxiety.  She was recently seen in the ED on April 4, 2021 with complaint of shortness of breath, nonproductive cough, fever, chills, nonbloody diarrhea, vomiting and weakness and subsequently diagnosed with COVID-19.  She had however received a second dose of COVID-19 a week before and was  discharged home due to lack of significant findings on imaging chest x-ray and lack of requirement for higher  oxygen support. She presented to the emergency via EMS for evaluation of progressive shortness of breath with associated with fever, chills, headache, persistent shortness of breath, cough productive of thick clear sputum, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea.  She denies abdominal pain, chest pain, or dizziness.  Denies recent antibiotic usage or recent travel.  Apparently, she thought she was getting better upon discharge after being kept for about 12 hours in the last ED visit, however she was not feeling well after going to bed last night and asked the husband to call 911.  Upon EMS arrival patient was saturating in the 80s and in respiratory distress.  She received 1 DuoNeb and was eventually placed on 10 L oxygen support.  She was noted to be in significant respiratory distress during speech.   Hospital Course Patient was admitted to hospital due to shortness of breath, and was found to have severe sepsis on presentation due to COVID-19 pneumonia.  She had evidence of acute on chronic hypoxic respiratory failure as well.  She was started on IV antibiotics, as well as remdesivir and Decadron at high dose.   Unfortunately she continued to have clinical deterioration, and ultimately required high flow oxygen therapy.  She was then transferred to the ICU, and ultimately required intubation due to severe profound ongoing hypoxia despite optimal medical treatment.  She did not respond to remdesivir or steroids or antibiotics.  Post intubation, she also developed acute renal failure during the course of her admission.   Multiple discussions were had throughout the hospitalization regarding goals of care, and initially patient and family wish to be continually aggressive.  She received full medical treatment, including life support, with minimal improvement.  Despite being on ventilator for roughly 5 days, she continued to have severe hypoxia.  She was proned, and was unable to sustain oxygen saturations when supine even for short period.   Her renal function continued to decline as well, and at that point discussion was had with family regarding goals of care again.  They were explained that symptoms continue to be persistent, and her illness continues to progress despite aggressive medical therapy.  Ultimately decision was made to not pursue dialysis, and to allow the patient to be kept comfortable and pass away naturally from this infection.   She was terminally extubated on 4/17 and passed away at 11:16 AM due to COVID-19 and acute on chronic hypoxic respiratory failure. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I felt dizzy right after the shot, but that may be normative. The adverse event was that approximately 1/2 hour after the shot, I developed numbness and redness in my ears than then traveled across my face and head. There was numbness and tingling that also began to affect my right eye. This episode subsided in approximately 1 hour. I did not see a doctor at that time. Across the week following the shot, I continued to experience numbness and tingling in the face off and on. I first went to a walk in clinic on 5/6/21 and my vitals were checked. A recommendation of trying an antihistamine was made in case the reaction was sinus related. The antihistamine did not appear to help. I saw my primary care physician on 5/12/21 with head/face numbness/tingling still continuing. She noted that this was called Paresthesia and prescribed 100mg of Gabapentin to be taken for two weeks. I am just beginning that treatment at the time of this report. My doctor recommended that I make a report to VAERS since this began right after my vaccine injection. Overall, at this time head/facial parensthesia and off and on dizziness has remained for 2-weeks since my first vaccination shot of Pfizer.
LAB_DATA: On 5/6/21 vitals were taken and were normal.  A test for vertigo was taken and vertigo was not indicated.  On 5/12/21 vitals were taken and were normal. A physical exam of reflexes and sensory sensitivity was taken. Motor control was normal in face and throat. Doctor visually noted some redness in ears on the pinna. Doctor did not think symptoms indicated a need to follow up with a neuro eval at this time, but I will go for a follow up exam in 3 weeks.

I received vaccine on Friday, April 23 at 1:10 PM. Over the next 3 days had a sore arm. The only other symptom was a heart flutter that lasted 20 to 30 seconds on 3 or 4 occasions.  On Tuesday, April 27, I again had a heart flutter, I felt like I was going to faint, my blood pressure dropped to 92/52 while sitting, my temples were sore, and I had a slight elevation in temperature of 1 degree.  I saw the doctor the next day, he ran: 1. blood work (it came back normal), 2. an EKG (which was normal), and 3. ordered a Heart Monitor (I began wearing it the morning May 7 and will wear it until May 21.) For three days my BP was off and on in the 90s/50s range most of the time and I did not feel the best. The doctor suggested that this may be related to my body adjusting to the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine, though he is not for sure that it is.  I had Covid at the end of January (1st symptoms  the 19th) and received the Regeneron monoclonal antibody infusion on January 22. . It seemed as though I recovered well within a few days- only a few Heart flutters during the first few days after the infusion.  I waited the prescribed 90 days prior to receiving the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was taking medication for hypertension. While it has been slowly getting better over the last year, it was still high enough to take meds, generally around 160/100 without. After the first vaccine it went very low, like 90's/50's, very rare for me. After second dose it went up and I took a pill that next day as it was 178/105. That night it went VERY low, and that is the last medication for hypertension I have taken. My BP has remained low, and most all nights it gets to the 90's/50's. PCP, Nephrologist, and myself are monitoring.   I also have had issues over last two weeks such as hot flashes/sweats (thought it was due to low BP), and started having blood in my urine last week, with some feeling like it was my period. I haven't had a period since my transplant 22 years ago, so this is odd and I have a dr appoint scheduled for next week to look into it.
LAB_DATA: BP is being tracked, and kidney function has remained level at creatinine 2.0 and eGFR at 25.

Patient is a 51-year-old male with a PMHx significant for hemochromatosis, sarcoidosis and morbid obesity who initially presented to the ED for evaluation of chest pain, cough and shortness of breath.   On presentation, vitals were mostly unremarkable other than some mild tachycardia and tachypnea.  Patient was able to maintain adequate oxygenation on room air but was placed on supplemental oxygen for comfort.  Blood work was mostly unremarkable.  ABG was not particularly concerning.  Troponin was negative x3.  Patient underwent chest CTA which showed basilar atelectasis bilaterally and scattered groundglass opacities and scattered borderline size hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes consistent with patient's known sarcoidosis.   Patient was treated with supportive care and monitored overnight.  He was able to maintain sufficient oxygen levels.  On the time my evaluation, patient continues to complain of bilateral rib pain worse with deep breaths consistent with costochondritis.  I discussed with the patient that he will need to continue to take NSAIDs on a scheduled basis to help with his discomfort.  Additionally I offered to prescribe cough medicine. I discussed possibly discharging the patient on steroids however he states that he makes a point to avoid taking steroids due to his history of hemochromatosis.  At this point, patient no longer requires care in the hospital and can be discharged home.  Patient is agreeable with the plan and all questions have been answered appropriately.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presents to clinic as Walk-In. Pt was scheduled on 5/12/21 to receive her 2nd COVID vaccine  Per Immunization note, patient received vaccine 5/12/2021 at 9:47:19 AM. Patient reports symptoms began about 5 minutes after receiving dose. Patient reporting initially feeling dizzy and then beginning to feel short of breath with an onset of chest pain.  RN went to check on pt in observation area and decided to Triage her in the RM. Pt was alert and  oriented x4 and speaking clearly, though having difficulty catching her breath. Pt pink in color, warm to touch, lips pink. Pt?s color appropriate for race. Pt was then escorted to Triage RM 1 via wheel-chair by I. RN who assisted her into the wheelchair.  At 9:50am  we checked the patient?s Vital signs:    Blood Pressure: 160/104 , Heart Rate : 89 beats per minute.  Pulse oximeter : 99%. No signs of edema or face or tongue swelling. EKG performed per Dr. and Report given to another Dr. who decided against giving any medications  to pt at this time.   -Pt reporting that she is feeling Short of breath and feeling palpitations in her chest.  -Pt is reporting having Chest Pain 10/10.  -Pt reporting feeling dizzy and lightheaded. -Pt reporting having ?starry vision? and having difficulty focusing her vision. -Pt reporting feeling pulsating pain in her right knee that radiates up her body to her neck.  Pt reports rating pain an 8/10. Pain worsens when pt?s right knee is touched. Pt reports that her veins in  her right knee feel ?full? and like ?blood isn?t passing through?. -No signs of edema or face or tongue swelling  Patient?s breath sounds are clear, bilaterally, auscultated anterior and posteriorly, upper and lower lobes.   Time: 10am   ;    Blood Pressure: 166/115    Heart Rate: 90   Pulse oximeter: 99 Point of Care completed. Blood Sugar checked and was 121 mg/dL.  Time: 10:01am: Complete Neurological exam check performed. -Patient alert and oriented x4. - Patient able to breathe on their own but feeling short of breath still. Pt on room air.  - Patient able to smile and frown equally bilaterally. - Patient?s speech is purposeful and clear. No slurring. - Patient able to lift upper bilateral extremities for 10 seconds at heart level. No arm drift. - Patient able to grasp and squeeze Nurse?s hands with equal strength bilaterally. - Patient able to push back and forth against Nurse?s arms with bilateral lower extremities.  Strength equal bilaterally. -Bilateral upper and lower extremity pulses examined. All Pulses equal and rated +3 (Normal). -No signs of edema or face or tongue swelling  Time: 10:10am   Blood pressure:  159/105   ;Heart rate : 91 beats per minute ; Pulse oximeter : 99% Paramedics entered the RM at 10:11am. Report given to Paramedics including a cover sheet,  list of medications and copy of EKG.  10:20am: Pt at this time is complaining of painful headache that feels like something is squeezing her head.  Pt also reporting feeling pulsations in her neck. Pt declines feeling chest pain anymore.  Pt reports that feeling short of breath and the new onset headache are her most prominent symptoms, besides still feeling dizzy and having ?starry? blurry vision. Paramedics leave with Pt to hospital at 10:25am. Pt awake and alert and speaking clearly and purposefully. No signs of edema or face or tongue swelling at any point.

Then over the weekend I experienced more red spots on my crotch and severe pain that kept me up at night and made me want to cry. I called the emergency line for the gynocologist and she prescribed something for a bacterial infection as well as for type 1 herpes. I then went in the following thursday and was seen again for the bumps. The bumps felt exactly like described in other cases i recently read about - shingles. I was in pain for 2-3 weeks and would use zinc and witch hazel and advil to try to get through the pain. It did eventually feel better and go away.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: within 12 hours of receiving my vaccine I had the usual symptoms (chills, aches, fever, nausea)  I took Tylenol for the fever.  However after that first 24 hours, the adverse reaction began.  I had constant dizziness, veritgo type symptoms and extreme fatigue.  I have now suffered with the vertigo and dizziness non-stop for the past 6 and a half weeks.  I went to three primary care doctors in my family practice, I saw 2 ENT's, my endichrinologist and my recenetly a neurologist.  I had a complete blood work up and various exams as well as a visit to the Urgent care and all of the medical professionals I have seen had said that this is an inflammatory reaction to the vaccine.  I was even prescribed a 5 day prednisone course which did not relieve the dizziness.  I have tried antihistamines, vitamin c, ibuprofen, and nothing can take away the symptoms.  I have also had ear fullness and pressure in my head with occasional tinnitus, and very foggy brained.  I have not been able to drive or care for my 2 year old or work during this time.
LAB_DATA: hearing test on April 8th 2020 was normal blood work taken on May 1st 2020 was normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am a pharmacist with 17 years of clinical experience and so medically literate. The night of the vaccine I had severe heart palpitations that woke me every 2 hours, but I managed to get some sleep. The 2nd night I could not fall asleep at all. I stayed up all night. 2nd night tried melatonin and benadryl, and only manged to sleep 2 hours very late in the night. This went on for a week. I saw a doctor and was given trazodone. It helped fall asleep but kept waking up every hour or 2 and then trouble falling asleep afterwards. So only managed 3-4 hours of sleep each night. I had side effects from Trazodone with mood changes so had to stop taking it. I saw another doctor based on a friend's recommendation who was going through the same issue. I was prescribed clonazepam 1mg. I was finally able to sleep a full night. I took it for 7-10 days and tried to taper back since I did not want to be dependent on it and wanted to go back to sleeping without  any sleeping aids. Klonopin 0.5mg seemed to be helping so on a follow-up appointment, I was given a months supply of clonazepam 0.5mg. I took that for a week and tried to taper that further and that did not help with sleep.  Amidst of this I started having tinnitus in the right ear and I never had tinnitus before. I don' t know if it was triggered by sleep deprivation, the vaccine or the clonazepam.  But I stopped taking clonazepam altogether after 3 weeks.  9 weeks out since the 1st dose and I can sleep a little on alternate nights only. And that sleep is fractured. So one night of almost no sleep and one night of 3-4 of hours of sleep if lucky. I tried benadryl and it helps a little but the trouble falling asleep is just as severe and continue to wake up every 2-3 hours. 8 hours in bed and only manage 3-4 hours of sleep. I skipped the 2nd dose due to continued issues with sleep. Looking for answers and guidance on how best to treat this and if/when this will be over for me.
CUR_ILL: None. Healthy male, biked/ran and exercised every day. No health issue or prior issue with sleep.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After I received the second shot on April 26th, I started feeling the side effects of chills, body aches and headache around 5 am the next morning which lasted for three days. LAB_DATA: The Physical Therapist may have taken notes to record the matter with my arm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Seen in office on 4/30/21 for abdominal pain, question of diverticulitis Hospitalized 5/3 for lower left quadrant pain and groin pain.  Had urine culture and CT abdomen/pelvis.  Admitted for observation, received hydration and medications for pain control.  Discharged next day. Seen by rheumatologist on 5/5/21 for severe left groin pain.  Otherwise her inflammatory arthritis appears to be no worse than before or perhaps slightly better.  Per rheumatologist, he is unsure if the left groin pain is related to rheumatoid arthritis and given the intensity and severity it could be unrelated. Had MRI of hip on 5/6/21 - results were normal Seen at Urgent Care on 5/8 - provider suggested pain could be related to rheumatoid arthritis flare due to COVID vaccination.  Per this provider, there is anecdotal evidence of apparent flares of gout and worsening of chronic autoimmune and rheumatologic conditions. However, that has been more typically in 2-3 time frame from immunization administration.  Patient was cautioned against assigning any definite causation.  Pt's pain has been very thoroughly investigated to date. I have first reassured them that I see no evidence for interim life or limb threatening process. Pain management is complicated by her chronic anticoagulation for afib, and by her reported dizziness with opioids. Although she has good ROM of her left hip without apparent provocation of pain, I still suspect this is primarily an arthritic pain flare. I have politely declined to prescribe any stronger opioid at this point. Pt, spouse, and I have discussed prednisone, with relative contraindication from her xarelto. She is desperate to try something else, and acknowledges increased risk of bleeding with co-administration.    They have asked my experience with post-COVID vaccination syndromes. I have discussed the anecdotal conversations among provider group re: apparent flares of gout and worsening of chronic autoimmune and rheumatologic conditions. However, that has been more typically in 2-3 time frame from immunization administration, and I have cautioned them on assigning any definite causation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the day after my second Covid vaccine (03/26/2021) I  had headache and fatigue.  On 04/10/2021, I started noticing a lot of bruising all over my body (petechiae and a lot of other areas of bruising) and I had a lump and pain behind my left calf.  I had some fatigue, but otherwise felt fine. I went to the Emergency Department on April11th thinking that my INR was too high since I?m on a blood thinner medication. The ER did an ultrasound of my legs and no blood clots were found. They did a CBC and I had a platelet count of 6,000. They admitted me, gave me a platelet transfusion and a steroid injection. They discharged me from the hospital on 04/12/2021 on 60 mg of Prednisone and to follow up with my hematologist, MD. My platelet count has since returned to normal.  I am having a CBC once a week and tapering off the Prednisone. Both Dr. and my Rheumatologist, MD believe that my severe drop in platelets were due to the Covid vaccine causing my Lupus to become very active and attack my platelets.  Please feel free to contact me if you have any additional questions. Thanks you,

SYMPTOM_TEXT: side note, not sure who is "tracking" this info for people with bad allergies who get the vaccines, so i will notate it here. both shots in left arm - shot 1 almost very top-mid on the deltoid, shot 2 so low on deltoid it was almost into the brachialis symptomology post each shot:    shot 1: arm pain that didn't really hit till day after injection, and lasted for a couple of weeks, with random pains down left arm. day of shot, some heart fluttering-like palpitations ~20min after receiving shot and vertigo, but gone quickly. didn't call over medical squad, because honestly couldn't tell if that was the POTS acting up, or reaction to the vaccine.   shot 2: no palpitations post injection, but again with the vertigo, while waiting in the parking lot post injection. had gatorade with me this time, so nipped that in the bud real quick. definite arm pain immediately post injection, that made it difficult to drive back home. but all of that was light compared to the next 48hrs. hit with flu like joint pain symptoms and fever, ALL over. from regular shoulder pain, to vertebrae to hips. even the metacarpal and metatarsal joints. VERY weird. i took tylenol and naprosyn, then went back to bed. i can stand high levels of pain normally, but the oddness of the locations along with the fever, made me just want to curl up in a ball. still have some residual pains and random high temp moments, but the intensity has lowered tremendously since that first 48hrs.   now, i would NOT call ANY of this 'an allergic reaction' to the vaccine. but it does seem to be hitting me harder than others, so figured it should be notated somewhere. husband has only really ever gotten arm and a little joint pain, with mild temp increase after the first shot. yep, i'm jealous, LOL.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 5 minutes after vaccination, I felt unwell. I sat with EMS that was onsite. HR was 160's, BP 160's systolic. Right arm went numb in first 5 minutes and my face went numb after 15 minutes post injection. After sitting 45 minutes with EMS my vitals stabilized and no numbness present. I walked to the car, sat in the car for 10 minutes and then I went into anaphylaxis. My airways began to close. My husband got the EMS on site and I was taken by ambulance to the ER. I was given IM Benadryl in the ambulance. In the ER I was given IV Benadryl and IV steroids.   After anaphylaxis event I had difficulty breathing for 3 weeks from enlarged lymph nodes. I had extreme shortness of breath for the 2 weeks following injection in that I had to crawl up the flight of stairs to the second level of our home.   About the 3rd week after injection, I began having full body itching  with no known stimuli. Only benadryl would treat it. I was on allegra or zyrtec daily. I would also develop 1 or 2 hives on my right arm.   4 weeks after injections I was reacting to food and drink. I could not drink alcohol- gin or vodka- it would result in full body itching and a few hives. I did a course of prednisone, and it decreased my allergic reactions and I felt almost normal for several months.  On May 8th, 2021 I had be experiencing great stress since February from a family member's cancer diagnosis. I had a crying event and immediately after I had an allergic reaction to gin, which had not occurred since the course of steroids.  Today is 5/13 and I have had 2 additional allergic reactions: one involving food and the other flowers. None of which I have ever been allergic to before. I have full body itching and I am now developing hives more often.
LAB_DATA: CBC done on 3/8/2021 in ER visit
CUR_ILL: none. Pervious numbness in arms and face after initial vaccination. PCP suggested I still get the second vaccine and I reported it.
PRIOR_VAX: First dose of Pfizer vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalization, on ECMO, deteriorating lung function - now on lung transplant list, hx. sarcoidosis.  Question of whether vaccination caused worsening of lung function / sarcoidosis.  Still currently hospitalized.  Transferred to our organization for ECMO.    Hospital Course: Patient is 62y.o. male with PMH of Sarcoidosis who presented to the hospital with worsening shortness of breath. Over the past 2 weeks, patient has had worsening shortness of breath on exertion and also while talking. On 4/23, patient noted intermittent fever, TMax 102F. Patient was seen by his PCP on 4/25 and started on a zpack, and was also seen in our ED on 4/25. He was discharged home with OP pulm follow up. Since then, patient has been feeling progressively worse, He noted 4/27, that his pulse ox was in the 70s with ambulation and that the cough and shortness of breath were worsening.    In ER, patient has been placed on 6 L of oxygen via nasal cannula. He was also febrile with TMax of 101.5 F. POC COVID-19 testing was negative. WBC was slightly elevated at 10.7, Na level was noted to be 129. PCT was negative. CTA PE protocol was negative for PE, there was significant interval progression of nodular and consolidative opacities throughout both lungs when compared to 2017, compatible with interval progression of sarcoidosis. Patient was admitted for further workup and management.   Patient's oxygen requirements gradually increased. He was initially treated with IV antibiotics and antifungals. He underwent extensive testing, including urine histoplasma, cryptococcal, respiratory viral panel which will negative. TB QuantiFERON was indeterminate, along with elevated IgM mycoplasma for which he received azithromycin. Patient was also placed on IV Solu-Medrol initially, transitioned to IV Decadron. Inflammatory markers were elevated. D-dimer was noted to be greater than 10,000, he was placed on therapeutic Lovenox dosing. Patient did have Covid testing which was negative, he was also vaccinated. His oxygen requirements continue to increase, he was eventually placed on BiPAP, although due to lethargy and increased work of breathing patient was eventually intubated and sedated. He was also started on paralytics. Patient was transferred to another hospital for possible need of ECMO or lung transplantation.
LAB_DATA: Sarcoidosis diagnosed ~2011 with bronchoscopy with biopsies. Procalcitonin was normal and WBC count initially normal.  Labwork significant for hyponatremia.  He was treated with ceftriaxone and azithromycin starting on 4/27.  Also treated with fluconazole.  He reportedly completed courses of these anti-infectives and is now off all antibiotics.  Initially on solumedrol 20mg every 8 hours. Later increased to Dexamethasone 10mg every 12 hours.  He did have a bronchoscopy on 5/6/21. PJP stain negative. Other cultures and serologies pending. Gram stain with rare PMNs. No organisms seen.  Mycoplasma IgM elevated at 1.24. Most recent blood gas 7.26 / 75 / 67 / 32. P/F ratio 83.    Previous PFTs 11/17/17 - FEV1/FVC 0.76, FEV1 70%, FVC 71%, DLCO 68%, TLC 75%, RV/TLC 98%. No significant BD response.
OTHER_MEDS: budesonide-formoterol albuterol HFA  rosuvastatin  cetirizine azithromycin

I'm not sure I'd describe this as adverse (in the sense that I did not require medical intervention, or haven't so far), but it was odd enough I thought to report it. My (male) partner and I just had my our second doses at 2PM today (it is 4:38PM as I write this). After receiving both the first and second vaccinations, I experienced what I can only describe as -- and pardon my phrasing here -- being as high as absolute balls. Like, just-ate-a-marijuana-edible high, only I had not used any marijuana in the 24 hours leading up to the event. I have used my electronic cigarette, but sparingly (those J&J lung blood clot stories were freaking me out), and while I am indeed on both Suboxone and Alprazolam, Suboxone does not produce a mental/physical high, especially in opiate-tolerant patients such as myself. Similarly, I took a much smaller dose of Alprazolam (about .25mg) which is less than 1/4 my prescribed dose, and I've been on anxiety meds for years -- suffice it to say that I was not "already high" upon arrival at the vaccine site.  What I experienced included a very strange sort of euphoria and brain fog. It was more pronounced after the first vaccine, but definitely noticeable this second time as well. Both times, my partner was entirely unaffected, which was great, because the effect was strong enough that I'm not confident I could have driven in that state. It is finally wearing off as I write this, but other female friends have reported similar experiences with the Pfizer vaccine, and since the J&J issues seem to affect women only, it may be worth further researching the effect of these vaccines on young females. I am also fairly petite (5'2, about 110 pounds currently) so that may play into it as well. Just wanted to give you all a heads up! I feel fine, but some ladies may need a "designated driver" for this vaccine, haha.
CUR_ILL: No physical illness, pretty debilitating mental illness
HISTORY: Scoliosis and resulting muscle unevenness in back, arachnoid cyst near cerebellum, depression, anxiety.

Patient DOD 4/19/21 Death Certificate Line A ?Adverse effect of Covid19 vaccine-5 day interval onset and death? Line B ?Anorexia nervosa? Line C ?Recurrent Major Depressive Disorder?  Received her second Moderna dose from our Mobile team on 4/14/21    Since then I spoke with Dr. (Mobile); clients PCP, several times regarding this event.  His nurse got an email from client on 4-12-21 that client had vaccination planned on 414 and may need to reschedule medical appointment planned 4-16 if she felt bad. The client was encourage to get vaccine and to keep appointment for Friday April 16th.  The client  emailed the office at approx 0300 Friday morning  April 16 to cancel appointment because she felt to poorly from vaccination shot to come in  (fevers; body aches). Dr next heard from police officer on Monday April 19th that she was found dead in her home. He requested the Medical Examiner (ME) evaluate but this request was denied. The client lived alone. Dr contacted family members but they did not have much interaction with the client and had no significant information to contribute. Dr said he speculates that the patients underlying anorexia nervosa likely put the client in a critical nutritional deficiencies / electrolyte imbalance condition and the side effects of vaccination were too much. He felt compelled to complete the death certificate as he did because the ME declined the case.   From vaccine mobile team notes:  team was there2-3:30pm. All the answers to the health screening questions for the patient were "no" except for "have you ever had a severe allergic reaction to something?" To that question the answer was "yes. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I administered the Pfizer COVID vaccine to the patient at about 2pm. I completed the vaccine, put the used syringe into the sharps container, grabbed the bandage, and turned back toward the patient. As I did this, he started slumping over in the chair, and his eyes rolled back into his head. I immediately put my arms around him so he wouldn't fall out of the chair. The patient's father was in the room as well and knelt down in from of him. The patient's body spasmed for a few seconds, then he came to but was breathing heavily and starting to sweat. I called to technician in the pharmacy and asked him to call 911 at 2:03pm.  I brought the patient a cool cloth and asked a technician to bring some water. The patient's breathing started to slow, but he was nauseous and dizzy. He dry-heaved once, and I put the garbage can in front of him. He slumped over the garbage can for a few minutes. Then he asked to lie on the floor. He seemed to do better lying on the floor. When the EMTs arrived, they attempted to have him sit in the chair again, but his dizziness returned, and he complained of being cold. The EMTs moved the patient to the gurney and transported him to the Hospital for further medical attention.

The palpitation episodes occur 2-3 times/week, and last from 2 minutes to 2 hours.    I contracted Covid-19 in March 2020 and had mild cold-like symptoms that lingered for around 6 weeks.  In June 2020, I began to experience the palpitation symptoms I am feeling now.  My symptoms subsided and disappeared from December through April of this year. Patient presented initially to his PCP on 4/24/21 for on going muscle aches after his COVID vaccine. Pain is on other arms, takes tylenol for treatment but no relief. Blood pressure elevated at the time of visit, no limited ROM, bruising present. Patient denies sx of cough, fever, SOB or chills, chest pain/pressure, GI or GU issues, HA.  Patient provided prescription for celecoxib 200mg PO daily prn pain.    Presented to hospital emergency room on 4/27/21 for chest pain, found to have anterior wall STEMI.  The patient was started on IV heparin and medical therapy with intravenous beta-blocker before being transferred to another healthcare facility.  His initial troponin was 0.2.  His CBC with diff and electrolytes are all within normal limits.  Patient was immediately taken to the cath lab for PCI. In route to hospital the patient was given 1 dose of nitroglycerin, aspirin, morphine for pain.  Cardiac catheterization was performed with placement of drug-eluting stent into the Mid LAD.  Patient started on aspirin and Brilinta.  Echocardiogram showed mild left ventricular hypertrophy, severe mid to distal anterior septal hypokinesis, apical akinesis with an EF of 45 to 50% and grade 2 diastolic dysfunction.  Patient has had no return of his symptoms since the PCI, tolerated p.o. intake without difficulty.  No nausea/vomiting, or shortness of breath.  Able to ambulate without difficulty.

On Thursday, 5/13/21, client received her first dose of Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine (LOT #: EW0184 exp: 8/2021) at approximately 9:24am on left deltoid. During assessment questions, client states she experiences "severe allergic reaction" to Bactrim and Sulfa and exhibits "anxiety and confusion." Client was to be watched in the Observation Area for 30 minutes after vaccination. Client's underlying medical conditions includes hypertension which she takes Atenolol and Losartan for; denies any other heart and respiratory diseases. At approximately 9:51 am, while waiting in observation area, client stated tearfully, "I'm not feeling well," and reported pain in her right lower back to EMT and RN. Client also reported to EMT and RN she tested positive for COVID-19  3 times back in March 2020, August 2020 and January 2021. Client also stated she had breakfast right before vaccination but did not take her daily medication for blood pressure this morning. Vital signs were initiated and taken every 5 minutes. At 09:51 am, (BP): 168/110 sitting, right arm; (HR) 77 bpm, no acute respiratory distress noted, client was alert, oriented X3, clear speech. At 9:05am, client was offered water and transferred to anti-gravity chair. Vitals at 9:06am: BP: 81/102 lying, HR: 72 bpm, client reported "feeling dizzy and weird." EMT and RN encouraged deep breathing and hydration with client. At 10:04 am, BP 169/111 lying, HR 75 bpm, client stated the pain in her right lower back was gone but was still experiencing "dizziness." At 10:12 am, BP: 157/105, HR: 71, client reported she was "feeling better, just really tired."  Client stated she did have her medications in the car. At 10:30 am, client was transferred from anti-gravity chair to a wheelchair with assistance from EMT and RN. She was accompanied to her car and was observed taking her medications and brought back to Observation Area for an additional 30 minutes. At 11:00 am, client was able to sit straight in a chair, and stated she was experiencing "no more dizziness" and she wanted to leave vaccination site. Client was educated by EMT and RN on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up on v-safe and importance of following up with her primary care physician. EMT walked client to her car without assistive device at 11:05 am.

I was diagnosed with Bursitis in the hospital two days later following a CT scan. I've received tramadol, percocet, and a corticosteroid injection.  I have a consultation with an orthopedic surgeon next week.  My shoulder was fine prior to the administration of the second vaccine, which seems to be due to poor technique by the nurse practitioner who administered it.

Patient reportedly went for a walk with his wife.  Upon returning home, he went to take the garbage out.  The patient was found down approximately 15 minutes later in his garage.  The patient's wife called 911 immediately?it is unclear if bystander CPR was initiated.  EMS was on scene within several minutes and initiated CPR.  The patient 3 shocks, and epinephrine.  ROSC was achieved at approximately 14:41.  At approximately 14:50, the patient again went into VF.  He received an additional  5 shocks, 1 mg of epinephrine, and 300 mg of amiodarone.  He went into asystole at approximately 1510.  ACLS was continued and the patient was given an additional 1 mg of epinephrine.  Upon arrival to the University of Minnesota cardiac Cath Lab, the patient remained in asystole with Lucas on.  He was cannulated on VA ECMO.  In the cardiac cath lab, he was found to have OM disease and diffuse CAD involving LAD Received intervention to his OM.  Initial LA was 14.3.  ABG 6.94/54/44/12.

Coronary angiogram: left-dominant circulation.               Left main: angiographically normal.               LAD: long 70% in the proximal-to-mid LAD; diffuse disease otherwise.               Cx: 100% occlusion of OM1; 80% left PDA stenosis.               RCA: 80% diffuse disease in a non-dominant vessel.    Percutaneous coronary intervention: - Successful PCI of the first OM with two overlapping DES (2.5x12mm and 2.25x38mm DES). I then had a warm sensation in my throat and started feeling like it was getting harder to breathe. I rolled down my Window, and looked for someone to wave over for assistance, but there were cars in the way, so I closed my eyes and focused on breathing deep and slowly to see if that would make it any better. After about 5 minutes my heart rate went back to normal, I felt I could breathe normally, and wasn't so light headed anymore. I should have reported this to someone when they told me I could leave, but I wasn't sure if it was an actual allergic reaction. Or if it was just a stress reaction. I felt like I should at least report it here, because I was completely fine before the injection, during the injection, and right after, until about 2 minutes after being parked.

36 Y male patient from another country with a past medical history significant for mild HTN (on 2.5 mg amlodipine) who was in his usual state of health until approximately 4/17/21 when he developed acute onset left volar forearm tingling sensation. He had received the Johnson & Johnson vaccine on 4/2/21 in his left arm and states that he did not experience any noticeable reactions after vaccination. He also recalls having had sustained a minor superficial scrape on his left volar forearm by a trash can lid when he had taken out garbage, which occurred very shortly before the onset of this tingling sensation. The tingling sensation then progressively worsened and became more diffuse across most of his body. He then developed fevers up to 102 at home, chills, neck pain, headache, and pain in all extremities (primarily arms but also in his legs).   He initially went to the Health Care ED on 4/28/21. He was afebrile at the time and his vital signs at that time were unremarkable with the exception of elevated diastolic blood pressures (90-104 mm Hg). WBC 10.1 with normal differential, electrolytes and liver enzymes within normal limits. Influenza, RSV, and SARS-CoV-2 PCR were negative. Urinalysis showed few bacteria but no WBCs. Chest x-ray was clear. Blood cultures were drawn and patient was then discharged.   Patient returned to the ED on 4/29/21 and reported fever to 102-103 d F, chills, nausea, weakness, body aches, and bilateral foot paraesthesias. He was afebrile (98.8) and his vital signs were within normal limits. His WBC was slightly elevated to 12.2 with a normal differential. His ESR was 11, CRP 1.5, CMP within normal limits. He was noted to have urinary retention and a foley was placed and he was given tamsulosin.    Patient then returned to the ED again the following day, on 4/30/21, with worsening generalized pain and weakness and difficulty walking.   ED course: temperature 101, heart rate 100s-110s, BP 140s-160s/70s-90s, RR low 20s, SaO2 high 90s. Labs remarkable for WBC 13.1 with 82.4% N, ESR 7, CRP 5.9, lactic acid 2.6, RF 10, urinalysis unremarkable, HIV antigen/antibody negative. Several imaging studies were performed. MRI T spine showed "Extensive cord signal abnormality in the cervical and thoracic cord as detailed above, with associated expansion of the cord (most pronounced in the cervical cord). Differential includes acute transverse myelitis, demyelination, infection (HIV, syphilis, other viruses)/parainfectious phenomenon, subacute combined degeneration, and inflammatory etiologies. An underlying mass or masses are not excluded but less likely given extensive multifocal patchy involvement. Recommend postcontrast imaging at this time for further workup. Consider brain MR as well to assess for systemic white matter disease."   A lumbar puncture was attempted in the ED but was unable to be performed.   Patient was given empiric IV ceftriaxone 1 g q24h and admitted to the hospitalist service. He was evaluated by neurology and was started on Solumedrol 1000 mg for acute transverse myelitis.   5/1/21 MRI brain showed "Multifocal patchy white matter signal changes, predominantly in the subcortical white matter, also present in the bilateral thalami and bilateral middle cerebellar peduncle, and redemonstration of extensive cervical cord signal abnormality and expansion. No associated restricted diffusion or enhancement. Broad differential, but given pattern of involvement findings are most concerning for ADEM (acute disseminated encephalomyelitis), other considerations include other demyelinating processes, toxic-metabolic pathology, or potentially atypical viral infection." Patient was given methylprednisolone for ADEM with transverse myelitis and clinically improved. He was hospitalized from 4/30/21 until being discharged to home in a wheelchair on 5/6/21.

As of this morning (Thursday), I no longer have a fever, chills, diarrhea or vomiting, but have intermittent stomach/intestinal pain and exhaustion/fatigue.

After getting my second vaccine, I instantly became tired and sore. I woke up in the middle of the night sick. I started with vomiting and diarrhea. My left arm was swelled and hurt. My body was achy and I could hardly walk. Swelling ended up going into my arm pit and left chest. That afternoon I had some trouble breathing along with chest pains. The pains lasted all day and then my throat became sore. I slept most of that evening. The next morning I woke up and my chest pain became a little worse, along w/a severe sore throat. My arms, legs, feet, and hands were very achy. I ended up going to the emergency room because I didn?t feel right. Returned home after they said that was normal symptoms after the shot. Within two hours, my face started swelling, throat hurt worse and I couldn?t swallow, and my lips were swelling.  I also had a rash in various places that itched pretty bad.  I ended up being covered in hives that were raised up like knots everywhere.  I returned to the ER and finally they said I was having an allergic reaction to the vaccine. I was hooked up to IV meds, then returned home. The next day (Sunday) my legs were swelling and it was very hard to walk.  The rash became worse and was popping up all over.  Didn?t feel like moving because my hand and feet hurt so bad. On Monday my leg was swelled double the size, hot and red. I was told they were worried about a blood clot, so I had blood work done. All of my levels were elevated, d-dimer was 2500. I was sent to Chillicothe Er to have testing done. They suspected blood clots in my lungs, however that came back ok. I was put on more meds and watched for awhile. After a CT scan and getting new meds, I left, but had to return to have a Doppler completed on my leg. It came back negative for blood clot, however the swelling still comes and goes. I ended up taking two kinds of steroids and a couple other meds to help the reaction. To this day, I am still tired easy, have some shortness of breath, my legs, feet and hands still swell and they ache pretty bad.
LAB_DATA: Bloodwork- twice  3/27/21 and 3/29/21; 3 trips to the ER; CT scan; Doppler on right leg

My twin sister -- who also got the vaccine with me (same batch) -- had fainted the night before. But her symptoms were not as intense as mine. My fever continued on and off for 48 hours.

Mom called EMS and when he awoke he stated he was nauseous.  After EMS arrived it was 2-3 minutes and he did not feel well again, he stood up and head fell back, eyes open, he was shaking, and making a gurgling noise again, this episode lasted 30 seconds. On May 8th, 2021 my mother went to get her Covid vaccine and today they called saying that she was given a bad vaccine. Today she said that the store kept calling and she was unsure why until she picked up and learned that she shot was bad. The pharmacist told her that the vaccine given to her was not stored at the proper temperature at the time of getting the shot. She told my mom that this location will no longer be giving the vaccine and that they could schedule her an appointment at a different place. They told her they were sorry for the inconvenience and said that they would mail her a $50 gift card. I don't understand how a $50 gift card can equal the value of a human life. I feel that if you are a licensed pharmacist then you should know how to store medicine and I feel that this is gross negligence. How many more people have received a bad vaccine from this place?  Now we have to worry about if her health is going to get worse due to this. What upsets me more is that it took them 4 to 5 days for them to even realize they had it at the wrong temperature.

Client ( DOB:7/19/1962) received the 1st dose of Moderna COVID vaccine lot #021C21A and expiration date 5/26/21 at 1:10PM.  Client reports having history of anxiety, so client was seated in a gravity chair prior to injection. PHN  was notified by Nurse student that client is having dizziness. PHN finds patient sitting upright in gravity chair, alert and oriented x 4.  Client reports feeling dizziness and feeling "hot" sensation. Client denies chest pain, blurred vision, no headache, or shortness of breath. Client reports having a history of high blood pressure, history of severe panic attacks, anxiety, and borderline diabetes.  Client is taking lisinopril, metformin, aspirin and Xanax. Client reports eating lunch.  Vitals are taken at 1:18pm blood pressure: 124/80, pulse: 68 and oxygen: 97%.  PHN offer client water, client accepted water. At 1:21pm vitals: blood pressure:126/78, pulse:65, and oxygen:97%.  Client reports "feeling dizzy" when looking into her purse for vaccination card and reports feeling a dry throat.  Client reports no shortness of breath and no other symptoms. At 1:26pm client reports needing to take her Xanax to prevent a panic attack.  PHN advised client if she could get someone to pick her up drive due to the medication she is taking, client reports she has been taking her medication for years and it never makes her feel unable to drive; client stated she had no one available to pick her up.  At 1:27pm vitals: blood pressure:128/80, pulse:60, and oxygen:97%.  Client reports no changes in dizziness and dry throat, even with water.  Client reports no chest pain, no shortness of breath, and no headache.  At 1:32pm vitals: blood pressure:120/84, pulse:60, and oxygen:98%.  Client reports no changes. At 1:37pm vitals: blood pressure 118/80, pulse:60, and oxygen:96%. Client reports no chest pain, no headache, no dizziness, no trouble breathing, Client states that she "feels the same."  Client also reports having a pacemaker placed 10/2020.  At 1:40pm, PHN offers calling paramedics since there is no real improvement in her dizziness and PHN educated client that it is unsafe to drive while dizzy.  At 1:44pm vitals: blood pressure:110/80 and pulse:61 and oxygen: 97%.  Client reports feeling relaxed.  PHN discussed with client importance of following up with primary doctor about lack of improvement in dizziness post vaccine. PHN provided client with ER precautions.  At 1:51pm vitals: blood pressure:116/80, pulse:60, and oxygen:98%.  At 2:03pm vitals are blood pressure:118/80, pulse:60, and oxygen:97%. Client denies any chest pain, blurred vision, headache, or shortness of breath. Client reports no change in dizziness.  PHN offer paramedics again and at 2:04pm PHN calls 911. Fire and paramedics arrive at 2:14pm to assume care.  Client signed AMA with paramedics.  Client stayed seated a little longer due to dizziness-educated client about following up with provider and cardiologist and provided client with Crisis & Access Line. Also educated client about dangers of driving while dizzy.  Client reports her dizziness is somewhat improved.  Client accompanied to car walked out with a steady gait at 2:35pm.
HISTORY: High blood pressure Borderline diabetic Anxiety Severe panic attacks

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per report from Observation RNs who witnessed reaction, RN'ss obtained history from both patient and patients mother.  P exatient plained history regarding last COVID vaccine where she needed the epi pen due to tongue swelling and stated that her "tongue swells with other things". She stated that she did not want the epi pen unless totally necessary.  She was accompanied by her mother. Approximately 5 minutes after patient arrived in the observation room, she stated she felt her tongue was swelling again. Patient felt warm and asked for a cool cloth. Patient alert and continued talking for the next 15 minutes. Mom stated that patient took Zyrtec today as recommended by asthma/allergy.  Mom stated that patient was premedicated with the zyrtec 1 hour before coming to the vaccine clinic. Pharmacy staff staffing the vaccine clinic, went to observation room to answer moms medication questions.  Mom asking if it was ok for patient to get a dose of benadryl now since she had taken the zyrtec 1 hour prior. Also mom asking if the liquid benadryl was dye-free.  Per pharmacy, liquid benadryl not dye-free so pharmacist opened and mixed 50 mg benadryl capsules and administered to patient. Patient asked for ice chips which she was given. Patient continued to be oriented, alert and talking.  No other symptoms present. Patient reported that her tongue did not feel as swollen as with the first COVID vaccine dose and mom agreed it did not look as swollen as last time.  Patient stayed for 1.5 hours total in the observation room and left ambulating with no issues.

Client rates headache 1/10 and left arm pain a 6/10 on a 1 to 10 severity pain scale. Client denies radiation of pain or numbness in left arm. Denies urticaria, hives, throat or facial swelling, chest pain, shortness of breath wheezing, weakness, palpitations or dizziness. Vital Signs at 12:18 HR 86, BP 110/72, SpO2 99% RA, RR 18. Upon examination, client appears in NAD and alert and oriented to person, date, place, and event. Left upper extremity with in normal limits. No bruising, swelling, bleeding, or redness notes. Client reports history of migraines and asthma as a child. Denies recent history of seasonal allergies, migraines and no longer uses an albuterol for treatment of asthma. Denies taking prescribed medications at this time. Education provided on side effects of vaccine and when to call a doctor for worsening or continuing arm pain. Pt reports symptoms of left arm numbness and nausea resolved at 12:32pm. Pt reports pain has improved to a 4/10. Vital signs at 12:40pm are HR 84, RR 14, SpO2 99% RA, BP 110/72. Client encouraged to follow up with PCP within the next week regarding symptoms experienced after vaccination.  Client verbalized understanding. ER precautions were given for throat or face swelling, difficulty breathing, palpitations, chest pain, dizziness, weakness or bad rash all over body. Client walked out of site with a steady gait. VAERS completed. VAERS confirmation number
HISTORY: None reported by client. History of asthma and migraines as a child.
ALLERGIES: Seasonal allergies. Client denied any other allergies.

We had sex again on Tuesday (day 3 of prednisone) and the hives started again but were not as bad as the first time. Today (5/13) I saw an allergist. She thinks I may be allergic to seminal fluid. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I suffered relatively severe reaction to the 2nd Moderna dose:  Very sore arm for 4 or 5 days, several hours of chills 14 hours after the injection, and swollen lymph nodes, including an egg-sized lump under the left arm that persisted for a week.  However, the significant event was a seizure 10 days after the injection.  This was a first seizure with no prior history or obvious cause.   Seizure began while I was asleep.  Wife heard odd noises, couldn't wake me and called 911.  I woke up in an ER hours later.  Neurologist said the MRI was clear, but EEG showed unusual activity in the left temporal lobe.  Prescribed Keppra (ongoing) and speculated that the seizure might be related to aging. He thought the timing of the event 10 days after the CoViD vaccine was coincidental.  However, I am reporting it out of an abundance of caution.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ?Moderna COVID?19 Vaccine EUA?    Sorry, I put my 2 vaccination above.... the second one was on February 11, 2021.... Moderna Vaccination Side Effects Report May 13, 2021  First Vaccination ? February 11, 2021 I did not have any effects the first week.  Then on the very same day of the week, in the following week, my arm, where I got the injection, got red and swelled up nearly from my elbow to my shoulder.  It was hot and hard and ached.  It was sore to the touch.  That was on Thursday.  On Sunday, I woke up OK, but as I dressed and started moving around, things did not feel right.  Soon, I knew that I was not going to be able to do the normal things of the day.  Within about an hour of being up from bed, I had a sever attach of vertigo.   I thought is was actually Vertigo, which I sometimes have, so I tried the ?exercise? that you can do to remove the debris from the ear canal and relieve the Vertigo?. This has worked for me in the past.  But, after trying it three times?. Barely being able to perform the procedure because of the severity of the Vertigo that I was experiencing, my daughter said that it might be from the vaccination.  She helped me to my bed.  I could not stand or move well.  Any time I moved my head or my eyes?even if they were closed? everything would spin more.  No matter what I did, I couldn?t the spinning to stop.  Finally, after I held my head and eyes very still, I fell asleep and slept for 7 hours straight.  When I finally awoke, the dizziness had begun to subside.  I slept for 2 more hours and started to feel more normal the next day.  The swelling and pain in my arm stayed for another 2 weeks.  Second Vaccination ? March 11, 2021 I had the injection in the afternoon and did not notice any real issues that day.  On the second day, when I awoke, I did not feel well?kind of dizzy and nauseous?.but not the Vertigo type of dizziness?just an off balance sort of dizziness.  Then I noticed that I couldn?t move or think very well.  It was like everything was in slow motion.  I tried to do the normal things of the day, but finally just gave up and went back to bed.  It was like my mind was watching everything go on in slow motion.  I slept the whole day again.  The next day I was mostly better, but after a couple of weeks, I started having frequent momentary dizzy spells.  They did not seem to be triggered by anything.  They just came and went.    The dizzy spells went on for several weeks? probably a month and gave way to another reaction that is difficult to explain because I have never had this experience before.  It is like when I move around or turn my head, my eyes do not go with me!  It is not a dizzy spell, although it does cause some dizziness.  And, my eyes do not go out of focus.  It is more like they are out of ?alignment? with each other or something like that.    It is very disconcerting and takes 1 to 3 seconds to come to correction.  It is happening more and more frequently.  That would be probably about 80% of the time that I move my body or my head.  It is now May and it does not seem like the side effects are abating.
OTHER_MEDS: Alendronate, MicroDaily with CoQ10(vitamin), AREDS 2, 42 Fruits & Vegetable Capsules (vitamin), Nattokinaise,  Citrus Bioflavonoids, Lion's Mane, Fish Oil

This has slowly improved over days 2 through 5.   - Nausea associated with the pain/tightness noted above   - Coughing (no phlegm)   - Vomiting (one more time on day 2 exactly 24 hours after the first vomiting episode)   - Fever and chills (both resolved by days 2-3)  Treatments:   - 500 mg Tylenol was used to treat fever and pain during the first several days.  Fever was well controlled, but pain was only partially controlled   - On days 3+ Advil was used for pain relief and it was effective   - Alka Seltzer Gold was used to treat nausea as necessary.  It was not particularly effective as the nausea seemed linked to the severity of the pain.  When the pain eased, the nausea did as well.   Outcomes:   - Symptoms have slowly improved over the 5 days post 2nd dose vaccination.  Advil has been discontinued since the afternoon of day 4.  No fever is present and the pain is now only mild.

My husband was sleeping the night of getting his 2nd Moderna Vaccination...  He, during his sleep, had a SEVERE Grand Mal Seizure with NOTHING leading up to it and NO PREVIOUS HISTORY WHATSOEVER of having ANY Seizures in his lifetime, nor ANY Epilepsy...  EVER! It was TERRIFYING, to me - I ran to his bedside (I happened to be in the livingroom watching television) after hearing loud grunts and a crash and came to find him convulsing, severely spewing blood and frothing at the mouth.  Grunting, convulsing, and thrashing.  Stiffening, arms and hands (both in a fist) tight and stiff in front of his chest, legs straight, rigid as a board and thrashing about spitting blood, eyes rolled back in his head.  As things began to becoming a little less severe, while waiting for the Fire Dept & EMTs to arrive I felt his legs which were hit to the touch and his face was drenched in sweat! With NEVER EXPERIENCING Anything like this before, and after 30 years of marriage, I thought my husband was dying ???????? He did NOT go with the EMTs, since once he was awake and somewhat cognitive we realized he was over it for the moment and we're in a wait and see basis. He saw our GP first thing the next morning.
LAB_DATA: Please contact our office, The Fire Dept and the Life Line EMTs for his vitals and any other information they recorded!
OTHER_MEDS: Had likely had a couple hits of Marijuana before bedtime...

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient post-vaccination (Pfizer/0.3ml/1st dose administered @10:23a) appeared to be seizing in his chair during observation @ 10:26a.  I rushed to him, requesting aid from his colleagues to help lay him on the ground and elevate his feet. He was unresponsive and disoriented, with shallow breathing and weak pulse, so I activated EMS @ 10:26a.  He appeared to seize again so I instructed two men to help roll him onto his side, at which time, an RN managing the vaccines, took over monitoring while I talked to 911.  EMS was on scene @ 10:29a. RN reports he'd had a vagal response, most likely due to witnessed severe anxiety during IM injection (name /right deltoid @ 10:23a). RN gave him Gatorade and he quickly became AOx3.  When EMS arrived, he was able to stand up, with assist, and be placed on the gurney.  EMS monitored him for ~ 20min onsite, at which time he became hypotensive, resulting in transport to the nearest ER with O2 and IV management.  Per HR representative for a business patient was discharged @ ~2p the same day, with diagnosis of severe dehydration and hypokalemia, his reaction most likely a vagal event.  Unknown if medications were given outpatient.

Friday, 4/16/21 woke up nauseous.  Worked all day.  Went to a store after work.  Felt nauseous did not eat dinner.  Around 9:30 PM arm pain from vaccine that I had been having got worse and my sternum hurt,  Got the chills.  I could not get warm.  Lied down in bed took my temperature...usually I am 98.6...I was 97.1.  After 2 hours I warmed up.  I was in alot of pain....feet, knees, legs, lower back, arms. neck hurt, were weak and stiff.  When I tried to get up from the bed..it was like my mind no longer knew how to "get up".  I tried to count, 1,2,3..get up on 3!! after many attempts I finally made it happen.  I was very unsteady and had to hold on to things.  Walking took a long time.  The bed and couch hurt to sit or lie on.  The only place to sit and feel like I could get up was on a tall stool on my kitchen island.  I used ice packs, cold showers, Tylenol, and topical creams.  I called my Primary care Doctor on Monday, 4/19/21 I was scared.  My legs ached at all times.  As of 5/1/21 I now have pins and needle sensations in my fingers and toes.  I have a pain in my neck to my jaw now when I chew at times.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt felt nauseous, hot, started getting red, and sat down on floor about 5 minutes after receiving the vaccine. I was alerted and I helped him into the vaccination room to lay down on the floor with his feet propped up. His girlfriend was there to help calm him down. I offered to call 911, he refused. I grabbed a fan for him, and turned it off when he requested. He then began shivering rather uncontrollably and said his left arm (injection site) was hurting and tingling, and at one point, said his right arm was beginning to tingle as well.  We had him breath and relax, he began to return to normal and he and girlfriend discussed how he must be partly having an anxiety/panic attack. He trialed standing up a few times until he felt good enough to leave the room, all in all about 20 minutes. He sat close by for additional 15 minutes of observation, at which point he left stating he felt more like himself.

On Thursday May 13th, 2021, patient arrived  to receive his first Pfizer vaccination. Patient was vaccinated and sent to the observation area.  At 1342, the patient stated," I feel dizzy, like I might pass out," to EMT observer. EMT observer immediately assisted the patient to the gravity chair. The patient's vital signs were taken: BP 110/72, HR 84, RR 15, oxygen saturation at 96% . The patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The patient was given water and stated, " I feel so much better after sitting in this chair." No loss of consciousness or syncope occurred. The patient was given a bottle of water.  Co-lead, assessed the patient, who was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation, was in no apparent distress, and was speaking in full sentences. No pallor or diaphoresis was observed.  Vitals were taken at 1347: BP 108/70, HR 63, RR 14, oxygen saturation at 99%. The patient took off his mask to reduce anxiety. Denied any history of fainting. or having any known drug allergies. Vitals were retaken at 1352: BP 120/68, HR 63, RR 14 ,oxygen saturation at 98%. The patient was offered a granola bar but denied it, as he ate around 1230. Patient denied any shortness of breath, blurry vision, lightheadedness, dizziness, itching, nausea, or facial flushing. The patient stated, " I feel totally fine."  Vitals were retaken at 1357, BP 120/70, RR: 14, HR 63, and oxygen saturation at 98%. Notified patient to inform the vaccinator about his reaction when returning for his second Pfizer dose. Vital retaken at 1402, BP 125/ 68, RR 14, HR 63, 98% oxygen saturation. The patient felt comfortable to drive home and left the site at 1405. The patient left the site with an even and steady gait.

To start, I had chicken pox as a child, 6 years old. On April 24, I had laser hair removal on my vagina - which I?m required to shave. The laser really gets into the skin, leaving it raw and open to infection.  I received my vaccine 5 days later.  I experienced chills, body aches for 2 days after, then the rash on vaginal area became extremely inflamed and red. I went to urgent care, doctor stated it did not look like genital herpes, but a skin infection.  The following morning, it was worst, so I went to medical facility, who swabbed it. Came back as HSV-2. A week later, i had blood work G and M, which showed no signs or Antibodies for HSV- 2.  I read an article that the vaccine is related to shingles activation.  From my understanding: A dermatome is the area of skin supplied by a particular nerve. The varicella zoster virus lies dormant in the cranial and spinal nerves. When the virus is reactivated, it travels along the affected nerves to the area of the skin served by those nerves, where it causes a distinctive, stripe-like rash. Which, was my vaginal area after intense laser.  Im also aware the the herpes zoster can be confused with gential, even in a culture that only test for hsv 1 and 2.
